{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778639803026,"sessionID":"ses_1e0ce96a4ffeI725GK5eP7uNWf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_kSXPnocFD2VOG1yUUc9MaJ2o","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (broken, n/a): Source-use predicates may gate load-use stalls, but must not zero RVFI rs fields because cosim expects raw instruction rs bitfields and pre-read regfile values even for architecturally unused operands.\n2: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (improvement, +24.81%): Moving rare DIV/REM operations from the combinational ALU mux into an iterative EX side unit substantially improves Tang Nano 20K fitness because CoreMark pays little CPI cost while the common integer/MUL path loses a large divider critical path.\n3: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +9.57%): Static backward/JAL prediction in IF can lose more to fetch-path immediate decode and target-add critical path than it saves from CoreMark loop-branch flush avoidance.\n\n(End of file - total 3 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (broken, n/a): Source-use predicates may gate load-use stalls, but must not zero RVFI rs fields because cosim expects raw instruction rs bitfields and pre-read regfile values even for architecturally unused operands.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (improvement, +24.81%): Moving rare DIV/REM operations from the combinational ALU mux into an iterative EX side unit substantially improves Tang Nano 20K fitness because CoreMark pays little CPI cost while the common integer/MUL path loses a large divider critical path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +9.57%): Static backward/JAL prediction in IF can lose more to fetch-path immediate decode and target-add critical path than it saves from CoreMark loop-branch flush avoidance.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778639803000,"end":1778639803024}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f856b4b587f2afa016a03e3ba32b0819babf91d1eb6290157"}},"id":"prt_e1f31913f001TQN7hn6Y56sBf7","sessionID":"ses_1e0ce96a4ffeI725GK5eP7uNWf","messageID":"msg_e1f316a81001lb4dGFKolOAq3O"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778639803460,"sessionID":"ses_1e0ce96a4ffeI725GK5eP7uNWf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_ggBmcEXRx6ZafY8vCv4j5E1V","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"category: micro_opt|micro_opt|hyp-20260512-002|hyp-20260512-001|hyp-20260512-003","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 4 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 1: {\"id\": \"baseline-bench-d11022f\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-13T01:44:34.902179Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Source-aware load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both\\ninstruction bitfields that look like rs1 and rs2, even when the following\\ninstruction does not architecturally read one or both sources. CoreMark has\\ndense load and immediate/control sequences, so false one-cycle bubbles can\\nreduce iterations per cycle without improving correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both\\ninstruction bitfields that look like rs1 and rs2, even when the following\\ninstruction does not architecturally read one or both sources. CoreMark has\\ndense load and immediate/control sequences, so false one-cycle bubbles can\\nreduce iterations per cycle without improving correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Make the hazard unit source-use aware for the IF/ID instruction. Keep the\\nexisting true load-use interlock, but only compare rs1 for instructions that\\nactually read rs1 and only compare rs2 for instructions that actually read\\nrs2. This should remove spurious stalls after loads for OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR,\\nLUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and SYSTEM encodings while preserving all real RAW\\nhazards and the existing RVFI retirement behavior.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive IF/ID rs1/rs2-use predicates from the opcode/funct class and gate the load-use dependency comparisons with those predicates.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Pass the full IF/ID instruction, or equivalent source-use signals, into the hazard unit instead of relying on unconditional rs1/rs2 bitfield comparisons.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive IF/ID rs1/rs2-use predicates from the opcode/funct class and gate the load-use d...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Move DIV/REM off the ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current execute stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU, including\\nSystemVerilog division and remainder operators in the same result mux as the\\ncommon RV32I and MUL operations. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely bloats LUT\\nusage and lengthens the EX critical path even though CoreMark is dominated by\\nordinary integer, load/store, branch, and multiply instructions rather than\\ndivide/remainder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current execute stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU, including\\nSystemVerilog division and remainder operators in the same result mux as the\\ncommon RV32I and MUL operations. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely bloats LUT\\nusage and lengthens the EX critical path even though CoreMark is dominated by\\nordinary integer, load/store, branch, and multiply instructions rather than\\ndivide/remainder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a small iterative\\nmulti-cycle M-extension side unit in EX. Keep ADD/SUB/logic/shift/compare and\\nthe MUL-family operations on the existing single-cycle path, but detect divide\\nand remainder opcodes in EX, start the divider, and stall the pipeline until\\nthe result is available. This structural decoupling should reduce the normal\\nALU critical path and LUT pressure with negligible CoreMark CPI cost because\\nrare DIV/REM instructions pay the added latency only when they occur.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real DIV/REM operators from the combinational ALU path while preserving ALTOPS behavior for formal builds.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add DIV/REM detection, launch/consume the iterative result, and hold the EX/MEM register while a divide operation is in progress.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\":...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken loop branch or JAL pays a two-instruction flush penalty. CoreMark has tight loops and frequent backward branches, making a very small front-end predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without the LUT and Fmax cost of a larger dynamic predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken loop branch or JAL pays a two-instruction flush penalty. CoreMark has tight loops and frequent backward branches, making a very small front-end predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without the LUT and Fmax cost of a larger dynamic predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a static predict-taken path in IF for aligned backward conditional branches and aligned unconditional JAL, while keeping forward conditional branches predicted not-taken and JALR resolved in EX. Carry the predicted next PC through ID/EX, compare it against the actual EX-resolved next PC, and redirect only on mispredict. This should remove most loop-back branch penalties with only immediate decode/add logic in the fetch path and no predictor RAM state.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles so EX can validate the IF-stage prediction while preserving RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode fetched branch/JAL immediates in IF and choose aligned pc+imm for backward conditional branches and JAL, otherwise pc+4; emit the chosen predicted next PC with the fetched instruction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Latch the IF-stage predicted next PC into ID/EX alongside the existing decoded instruction metadata.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage....","metadata":{"matches":4,"truncated":false},"title":"category: micro_opt|micro_opt|hyp-20260512-002|hyp-20260512-001|hyp-20260512-003","time":{"start":1778639803442,"end":1778639803459}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f856b4b587f2afa016a03e3ba32c0819b8d062fb423c6d762"}},"id":"prt_e1f3192c7001i9tLdEguVLWFaB","sessionID":"ses_1e0ce96a4ffeI725GK5eP7uNWf","messageID":"msg_e1f316a81001lb4dGFKolOAq3O"}}
