{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778639850695,"sessionID":"ses_1e0ce96a4ffeI725GK5eP7uNWf","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_qdCFxTJDyFvqVgBeWTIGaH54","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-001-r2s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\n+title: \"Collapse ALU multiply products\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The post-DIV baseline still computes three independent 64-bit multiplier\n+  products in the combinational ALU: unsigned*unsigned, signed*signed, and\n+  signed*unsigned. CoreMark benefits from keeping MUL single-cycle, but the\n+  extra high-half multiplier hardware likely costs LUTs, routing, and Fmax on\n+  the Tang Nano 20K even when only one M-extension result is selected.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace the three parallel ALU multiplier products with one unsigned 32x32\n+  product plus high-half sign-correction subtractors. The low 32 bits are\n+  identical for MUL under any signedness; MULHU uses the raw high half; MULH\n+  subtracts the opposite operand from the high half for each negative input;\n+  and MULHSU subtracts the unsigned multiplier operand when rs1 is negative.\n+  This preserves the existing single-cycle M-extension CPI while reducing\n+  replicated multiplier logic and routing pressure on the ALU result path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Compute one unsigned product and derive MULH/MULHSU high halves with RV32M-correct sign-correction logic instead of instantiating three parallel products.\"\n+  - file: test/test_alu.py\n+    description: \"Add focused MULH and MULHSU edge vectors covering negative operands, INT_MIN, all-ones, and mixed signed/unsigned correction cases.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/e