{"type":"text","timestamp":1778639874451,"sessionID":"ses_1e0ce963cffedB7dQvg85edi48","part":{"id":"prt_e1f32a771001oli8clfAQlmPS0","messageID":"msg_e1f31d1bc001wJYX1NMu2j0wqN","sessionID":"ses_1e0ce963cffedB7dQvg85edi48","type":"text","text":"I’m writing the YAML hypothesis now. The proposed structural change is a small front-end fetch queue/skid buffer that lets instruction fetch run ahead while decode/back-end are stalled, which targets the random iStall+dStall CoreMark mode without changing retirement width or eval contracts.","time":{"start":1778639873905,"end":1778639874450},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_08fc3eb05cc32bec016a03e401a240819b9e1c81f5f76789dd","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778639881638,"sessionID":"ses_1e0ce963cffedB7dQvg85edi48","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_GUc3NGnofufKdmPxAae4Ra6G","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r2s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\n+title: \"Decoupled fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end is tightly coupled to the rest of the pipeline: any\n+  dmem stall, load-use stall, divide stall, or raw imem-not-ready cycle holds\n+  the PC and prevents useful fetch progress. In the tournament CoreMark mode\n+  both instruction and data ports see random backpressure, so exposed fetch\n+  bubbles reduce iterations per cycle even when the instruction port could\n+  have fetched ahead during unrelated back-end stalls.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a tiny two-entry fetch skid buffer between IF and ID. The IF stage should\n+  keep issuing sequential fetches while the decode/back-end side is stalled and\n+  there is queue space, and ID should consume from the queue whenever it can\n+  advance. Redirects still flush the queue and restart at the resolved target,\n+  preserving the current EX-resolution semantics and RVFI ordering. This\n+  structural decoupling should hide a fraction of random imem stalls behind\n+  dmem/load-use/div stalls with modest LUT/FF cost and less timing risk than\n+  putting branch prediction logic back on the fetch critical path.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the purely combinational IF/ID payload with a small valid-ready fetch queue that can fill while ID is stalled, drains to ID when available, and flushes on redirect.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Base front-end stalls on fetch-queue empty/full status instead of raw imemReady, allowing decode to proceed from buffered instructions during imem backpressure.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the fetch queue status into the existing hazard/control path while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port set and single-retire channel behavior.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r2s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r2s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r2s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260512-002-r2s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@\n+id: hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\n+title: \"Decoupled fetch skid buffer\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end is tightly coupled to the rest of the pipeline: any\n+  dmem stall, load-use stall, divide stall, or raw imem-not-ready cycle holds\n+  the PC and prevents useful fetch progress. In the tournament CoreMark mode\n+  both instruction and data ports see random backpressure, so exposed fetch\n+  bubbles reduce iterations per cycle even when the instruction port could\n+  have fetched ahead during unrelated back-end stalls.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a tiny two-entry fetch skid buffer between IF and ID. The IF stage should\n+  keep issuing sequential fetches while the decode/back-end side is stalled and\n+  there is queue space, and ID should consume from the queue whenever it can\n+  advance. Redirects still flush the queue and restart at the resolved target,\n+  preserving the current EX-resolution semantics and RVFI ordering. This\n+  structural decoupling should hide 