{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778651541048,"sessionID":"ses_1e01b7558ffey1JQ9pYmA0GhMu","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_oVKe7Iddi1fR6q6AuUeAuvO4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":2000},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (broken, n/a): Source-use predicates may gate load-use stalls, but must not zero RVFI rs fields because cosim expects raw instruction rs bitfields and pre-read regfile values even for architecturally unused operands.\n2: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (improvement, +24.81%): Moving rare DIV/REM operations from the combinational ALU mux into an iterative EX side unit substantially improves Tang Nano 20K fitness because CoreMark pays little CPI cost while the common integer/MUL path loses a large divider critical path.\n3: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +9.57%): Static backward/JAL prediction in IF can lose more to fetch-path immediate decode and target-add critical path than it saves from CoreMark loop-branch flush avoidance.\n4: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -2.76%): Collapsing MULH/MULHU/MULHSU to one unsigned product plus high-half sign-correction subtractors can hurt Tang Nano 20K fitness because the added subtractor chain sits on the selected multiplier result path while parallel inferred multipliers are handled efficiently.\n5: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -17.61%): A two-entry IF skid buffer can cost more than it hides on CoreMark because queue_full/queue_empty/consume control and bypass timing outweigh limited fetch-ahead benefit under this single-issue front end.\n6: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -38.35%): Even a tiny IF-stage BTB can lose badly when tag compare/counter/target lookup becomes the fetch next-PC path, so CoreMark branch-penalty wins are not enough unless prediction metadata is off the Fmax-critical front end.\n7: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (regression, -3.35%): Source-aware load-use gating can regress when the added IF/ID opcode decode plus WB-stage RVFI source-value repair costs more Fmax/control complexity than CoreMark saves from eliminating false load bubbles.\n8: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -2.61%): Simply inserting an IF/ID register can regress because the new stall/flush/frontend_hold muxing and redirect-invalid handling outweigh breaking the imem_data-to-decode path unless retiming also simplifies front-end control.\n9: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (regression, -40.93%): Moving static prediction to ID still creates a same-cycle decode/immediate-add/stall-gated redirect into the IF PC mux, so the front-end critical path remains while EX also pays predicted-PC compare/correction logic.\n10: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r4s0 (improvement, +7.78%): Replacing MEM-stage variable shifts with explicit addr[1:0] byte-lane case muxes improves Tang Nano 20K fitness because CoreMark’s load/store-heavy path benefits from smaller dmem_rdata-to-WB and address-to-mask mux trees.\n11: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r4s1 (regression, -3.44%): Moving MULH/MULHU/MULHSU into an EX side unit can lose because low-half MUL still keeps the multiplier on the common path while high_mul stall/start/result muxing adds control cost that outweighs removing rare high-half product selection.\n12: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r4s2 (regression, -10.45%): Even a single-entry backward-loop predictor with a registered target can regress because the IF PC compare/target mux plus always-on EX predicted-next-PC correction cost more than CoreMark saves from repeat loop-back hits.\n13: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r5s0 (regression, -0.24%): Removing the regfile bulk reset did not improve Tang Nano 20K fitness, suggesting reset fanout/muxing on x1-x31 is not the binding path compared with the core's active decode, memory, and ALU datapaths.\n14: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r5s2 (regression, -48.07%): A return-only JALR target predictor is too narrow for CoreMark here; the IF PC compare/target mux plus carried predicted-PC EX correction cost overwhelms any saved return flushes.\n15: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r6s0 (regression, -4.12%): Pruning unused late-stage ctrl_t fields can regress because EX/MEM and MEM/WB control flops are not the binding path, while extra narrow-struct repacking and trap muxing add always-active control logic.\n16: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r6s1 (regression, +2.37%): MEM-stage load-data bypassing can regress when aligned dmem_rdata feeds directly into EX operand muxes, lengthening the memory-to-ALU path more than CoreMark benefits from removing one-cycle load-use bubbles.\n17: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r6s2 (improvement, +7.25%): A hot-branch predictor can pay off when the tag compare is shifted into a one-cycle sequential lookahead and the IF next-PC mux consumes only a registered prearmed target, preserving Fmax while recovering CoreMark loop-back bubbles.\n18: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r7s0 (regression, -22.32%): Deleting dead branch_taken/branch_target fields from EX/MEM can still hurt Tang Nano 20K fitness, reinforcing that late pipeline register width is not the binding path and small typedef changes may perturb packing/placement more than timing.\n19: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r7s1 (regression, -19.86%): Precomputing load/store masks, replicated wdata, aligned RVFI addr, and misalignment trap control in EX can hurt once MEM byte-lane muxing is simplified, because it shifts address-dependent gating onto the EX effective-address/control path rather than removing the true bottleneck.\n20: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r7s2 (regression, -22.20%): Expanding the registered lookahead predictor from one to two entries can lose because extra seq_pc tag compares, target priority muxing, and replacement state add IF arming complexity beyond CoreMark's remaining hot-edge thrash benefit.\n21: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r8s0 (regression, -53.91%): Forward direct JAL updates are not mere pollution for the one-entry registered lookahead predictor; filtering it to only backward targets can erase useful CoreMark call-site prediction and badly reduce fitness.\n22: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r8s1 (regression, -20.41%): Precomputing PC-relative adders in ID can regress when decode already sits on an active path; extra pc_plus4/pc_plus_imm adders and wider ID/EX flops may cost more than removing EX-side branch/JAL/AUIPC target adds.\n23: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r9s0 (regression, -16.56%): Special-casing MEM halfword masks/loads to addr[1] can regress despite architecturally unreachable misaligned lanes, suggesting the broader addr[1:0] case mux mapped better than the narrower aligned-only logic on this CoreMark path.\n24: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r9s1 (regression, -16.34%): Moving all MUL variants into an EX side unit regresses because CoreMark's low-half MUL frequency plus mul_wait/ex_busy stall control costs more than removing inferred multipliers from the common ALU mux.\n25: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r9s2 (regression, -6.38%): Requiring a second resolved hit before replacing the one-entry registered lookahead predictor can lose because delayed promotion sacrifices useful immediate CoreMark call/loop predictions while adding EX-update compare state without relieving the IF registered-target path.\n26: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r10s0 (regression, -11.10%): Replacing the EX predictor-update `branch_target < in.pc` comparator with `in.imm[31]` regressed, suggesting that compare was not the timing bottleneck and imm-bit/control remapping can perturb the hot predictor path more than it simplifies it.\n27: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r10s1 (regression, -10.06%): A single-entry store-drain buffer can cost more than it hides because store_buf_pending/dmem_ready arbitration lengthens MEM-stage dmem control and global stall logic while conservative CoreMark memory ordering leaves limited independent work under random store backpressure.\n28: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r10s2 (regression, -7.29%): Training the one-entry registered lookahead predictor on all taken conditional branches likely pollutes its hot loop/call target with forward biased branches, so the backward-branch direction filter is useful capacity management rather than just update-path complexity.\n\n(End of file - total 28 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (broken, n/a): Source-use predicates may gate load-use stalls, but must not zero RVFI rs fields because cosim expects raw instruction rs bitfields and pre-read regfile values even for architecturally unused operands.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (improvement, +24.81%): Moving rare DIV/REM operations from the combinational ALU mux into an iterative EX side unit substantially improves Tang Nano 20K fitness because CoreMark pays little CPI cost while the common integer/MUL path loses a large divider critical path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +9.57%): Static backward/JAL prediction in IF can lose more to fetch-path immediate decode and target-add critical path than it saves from CoreMark loop-branch flush avoidance.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -2.76%): Collapsing MULH/MULHU/MULHSU to one unsigned product plus high-half sign-correction subtractors can hurt Tang Nano 20K fitness because the added subtractor chain sits on the selected multiplier result path while parallel inferred multipliers are handled efficiently.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -17.61%): A two-entry IF skid buffer can cost more than it hides on CoreMark because queue_full/queue_empty/consume control and bypass timing outweigh limited fetch-ahead benefit under this single-issue front end.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -38.35%): Even a tiny IF-stage BTB can lose badly when tag compare/counter/target lookup becomes the fetch next-PC path, so CoreMark branch-penalty wins are not enough unless prediction metadata is off the Fmax-critical front end.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (regression, -3.35%): Source-aware load-use gating can regress when the added IF/ID opcode decode plus WB-stage RVFI source-value repair costs more Fmax/control complexity than CoreMark saves from eliminating false load bubbles.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -2.61%): Simply inserting an IF/ID register can regress because the new stall/flush/frontend_hold muxing and redirect-invalid handling outweigh breaking the imem_data-to-decode path unless retiming also simplifies front-end control.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (regression, -40.93%): Moving static prediction to ID still creates a same-cycle decode/immediate-add/stall-gated redirect into the IF PC mux, so the front-end critical path remains while EX also pays predicted-PC compare/correction logic.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r4s0 (improvement, +7.78%): Replacing MEM-stage variable shifts with explicit addr[1:0] byte-lane case muxes improves Tang Nano 20K fitness because CoreMark’s load/store-heavy path benefits from smaller dmem_rdata-to-WB and address-to-mask mux trees.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r4s1 (regression, -3.44%): Moving MULH/MULHU/MULHSU into an EX side unit can lose because low-half MUL still keeps the multiplier on the common path while high_mul stall/start/result muxing adds control cost that outweighs removing rare high-half product selection.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r4s2 (regression, -10.45%): Even a single-entry backward-loop predictor with a registered target can regress because the IF PC compare/target mux plus always-on EX predicted-next-PC correction cost more than CoreMark saves from repeat loop-back hits.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r5s0 (regression, -0.24%): Removing the regfile bulk reset did not improve Tang Nano 20K fitness, suggesting reset fanout/muxing on x1-x31 is not the binding path compared with the core's active decode, memory, and ALU datapaths.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r5s2 (regression, -48.07%): A return-only JALR target predictor is too narrow for CoreMark here; the IF PC compare/target mux plus carried predicted-PC EX correction cost overwhelms any saved return flushes.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r6s0 (regression, -4.12%): Pruning unused late-stage ctrl_t fields can regress because EX/MEM and MEM/WB control flops are not the binding path, while extra narrow-struct repacking and trap muxing add always-active control logic.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r6s1 (regression, +2.37%): MEM-stage load-data bypassing can regress when aligned dmem_rdata feeds directly into EX operand muxes, lengthening the memory-to-ALU path more than CoreMark benefits from removing one-cycle load-use bubbles.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r6s2 (improvement, +7.25%): A hot-branch predictor can pay off when the tag compare is shifted into a one-cycle sequential lookahead and the IF next-PC mux consumes only a registered prearmed target, preserving Fmax while recovering CoreMark loop-back bubbles.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r7s0 (regression, -22.32%): Deleting dead branch_taken/branch_target fields from EX/MEM can still hurt Tang Nano 20K fitness, reinforcing that late pipeline register width is not the binding path and small typedef changes may perturb packing/placement more than timing.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r7s1 (regression, -19.86%): Precomputing load/store masks, replicated wdata, aligned RVFI addr, and misalignment trap control in EX can hurt once MEM byte-lane muxing is simplified, because it shifts address-dependent gating onto the EX effective-address/control path rather than removing the true bottleneck.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r7s2 (regression, -22.20%): Expanding the registered lookahead predictor from one to two entries can lose because extra seq_pc tag compares, target priority muxing, and replacement state add IF arming complexity beyond CoreMark's remaining hot-edge thrash benefit.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778651541035,"end":1778651541047}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06a33425d8edd2ba016a041194dcf0819abec78cc1b012e334"}},"id":"prt_e1fe4ae270011CQkcmvrZAu5wL","sessionID":"ses_1e01b7558ffey1JQ9pYmA0GhMu","messageID":"msg_e1fe48b0a001lZTRXPZPl7FsDi"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778651541055,"sessionID":"ses_1e01b7558ffey1JQ9pYmA0GhMu","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_J4jxomSt0sso8RQqMx1ubFRV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"micro_opt|micro-opt|ALU|forward|regfile|decode|hazard|mask|load|MUL|DIV|critical|Fmax","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 31 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 1: {\"id\": \"baseline-bench-d11022f\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-13T01:44:34.902179Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n\n  Line 2: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r1s0\", \"title\": \"Source-aware load-use stalls\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both\\ninstruction bitfields that look like rs1 and rs2, even when the following\\ninstruction does not architecturally read one or both sources. CoreMark has\\ndense load and immediate/control sequences, so false one-cycle bubbles can\\nreduce iterations per cycle without improving correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use interlock compares a load destination against both\\ninstruction bitfields that look like rs1 and rs2, even when the following\\ninstruction does not architecturally read one or both sources. CoreMark has\\ndense load and immediate/control sequences, so false one-cycle bubbles can\\nreduce iterations per cycle without improving correctness.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Make the hazard unit source-use aware for the IF/ID instruction. Keep the\\nexisting true load-use interlock, but only compare rs1 for instructions that\\nactually read rs1 and only compare rs2 for instructions that actually read\\nrs2. This should remove spurious stalls after loads for OP-IMM, LOAD, JALR,\\nLUI, AUIPC, JAL, FENCE, and SYSTEM encodings while preserving all real RAW\\nhazards and the existing RVFI retirement behavior.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive IF/ID rs1/rs2-use predicates from the opcode/funct class and gate the load-use dependency comparisons with those predicates.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Pass the full IF/ID instruction, or equivalent source-use signals, into the hazard unit instead of relying on unconditional rs1/rs2 bitfield comparisons.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive IF/ID rs1/rs2-use predicates from the opcode/funct class and gate the load-use d...\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Move DIV/REM off the ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current execute stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU, including\\nSystemVerilog division and remainder operators in the same result mux as the\\ncommon RV32I and MUL operations. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely bloats LUT\\nusage and lengthens the EX critical path even though CoreMark is dominated by\\nordinary integer, load/store, branch, and multiply instructions rather than\\ndivide/remainder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current execute stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU, including\\nSystemVerilog division and remainder operators in the same result mux as the\\ncommon RV32I and MUL operations. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely bloats LUT\\nusage and lengthens the EX critical path even though CoreMark is dominated by\\nordinary integer, load/store, branch, and multiply instructions rather than\\ndivide/remainder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a small iterative\\nmulti-cycle M-extension side unit in EX. Keep ADD/SUB/logic/shift/compare and\\nthe MUL-family operations on the existing single-cycle path, but detect divide\\nand remainder opcodes in EX, start the divider, and stall the pipeline until\\nthe result is available. This structural decoupling should reduce the normal\\nALU critical path and LUT pressure with negligible CoreMark CPI cost because\\nrare DIV/REM instructions pay the added latency only when they occur.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real DIV/REM operators from the combinational ALU path while preserving ALTOPS behavior for formal builds.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add DIV/REM detection, launch/consume the iterative result, and hold the EX/MEM register while a divide operation is in progress.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\":...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken loop branch or JAL pays a two-instruction flush penalty. CoreMark has tight loops and frequent backward branches, making a very small front-end predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without the LUT and Fmax cost of a larger dynamic predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken loop branch or JAL pays a two-instruction flush penalty. CoreMark has tight loops and frequent backward branches, making a very small front-end predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without the LUT and Fmax cost of a larger dynamic predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a static predict-taken path in IF for aligned backward conditional branches and aligned unconditional JAL, while keeping forward conditional branches predicted not-taken and JALR resolved in EX. Carry the predicted next PC through ID/EX, compare it against the actual EX-resolved next PC, and redirect only on mispredict. This should remove most loop-back branch penalties with only immediate decode/add logic in the fetch path and no predictor RAM state.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles so EX can validate the IF-stage prediction while preserving RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode fetched branch/JAL immediates in IF and choose aligned pc+imm for backward conditional branches and JAL, otherwise pc+4; emit the chosen predicted next PC with the fetched instruction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Latch the IF-stage predicted next PC into ID/EX alongside the existing decoded instruction metadata.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage....\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Collapse ALU multiply products\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The post-DIV baseline still computes three independent 64-bit multiplier\\nproducts in the combinational ALU: unsigned*unsigned, signed*signed, and\\nsigned*unsigned. CoreMark benefits from keeping MUL single-cycle, but the\\nextra high-half multiplier hardware likely costs LUTs, routing, and Fmax on\\nthe Tang Nano 20K even when only one M-extension result is selected.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The post-DIV baseline still computes three independent 64-bit multiplier\\nproducts in the combinational ALU: unsigned*unsigned, signed*signed, and\\nsigned*unsigned. CoreMark benefits from keeping MUL single-cycle, but the\\nextra high-half multiplier hardware likely costs LUTs, routing, and Fmax on\\nthe Tang Nano 20K even when only one M-extension result is selected.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the three parallel ALU multiplier products with one unsigned 32x32\\nproduct plus high-half sign-correction subtractors. The low 32 bits are\\nidentical for MUL under any signedness; MULHU uses the raw high half; MULH\\nsubtracts the opposite operand from the high half for each negative input;\\nand MULHSU subtracts the unsigned multiplier operand when rs1 is negative.\\nThis preserves the existing single-cycle M-extension CPI while reducing\\nreplicated multiplier logic and routing pressure on the ALU result path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute one unsigned product and derive MULH/MULHSU high halves with RV32M-correct sign-correction logic instead of instantiating three parallel products.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Add focused MULH and MULHSU edge vectors covering negative operands, INT_MIN, all-ones, and mixed signed/unsigned correction cases.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"de...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Decoupled fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end is tightly coupled to the rest of the pipeline: any\\ndmem stall, load-use stall, divide stall, or raw imem-not-ready cycle holds\\nthe PC and prevents useful fetch progress. In the tournament CoreMark mode\\nboth instruction and data ports see random backpressure, so exposed fetch\\nbubbles reduce iterations per cycle even when the instruction port could\\nhave fetched ahead during unrelated back-end stalls.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end is tightly coupled to the rest of the pipeline: any\\ndmem stall, load-use stall, divide stall, or raw imem-not-ready cycle holds\\nthe PC and prevents useful fetch progress. In the tournament CoreMark mode\\nboth instruction and data ports see random backpressure, so exposed fetch\\nbubbles reduce iterations per cycle even when the instruction port could\\nhave fetched ahead during unrelated back-end stalls.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny two-entry fetch skid buffer between IF and ID. The IF stage should\\nkeep issuing sequential fetches while the decode/back-end side is stalled and\\nthere is queue space, and ID should consume from the queue whenever it can\\nadvance. Redirects still flush the queue and restart at the resolved target,\\npreserving the current EX-resolution semantics and RVFI ordering. This\\nstructural decoupling should hide a fraction of random imem stalls behind\\ndmem/load-use/div stalls with modest LUT/FF cost and less timing risk than\\nputting branch prediction logic back on the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the purely combinational IF/ID payload with a small valid-ready fetch queue that can fill while ID is stalled, drains to ID when available, and flushes on redirect.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Base front-end stalls ...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny BTB branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so tight CoreMark\\nloops pay a two-instruction redirect penalty on each taken iteration. The prior\\nstatic backward predictor showed that avoiding these penalties can help CPI,\\nbut its IF-stage immediate decode and target add hurt Fmax enough to lose most\\nof the gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so tight CoreMark\\nloops pay a two-instruction redirect penalty on each taken iteration. The prior\\nstatic backward predictor showed that avoiding these penalties can help CPI,\\nbut its IF-stage immediate decode and target add hurt Fmax enough to lose most\\nof the gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small direct-mapped BTB with 2-bit saturating counters, updated only from\\nresolved control-flow instructions in EX. IF predicts taken only on a valid tag\\nhit with a taken counter and uses the stored target, otherwise it fetches pc+4;\\nthis keeps branch immediate decode and target addition out of the fetch path.\\nCarry predicted next-PC metadata through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX redirects only\\nwhen the stored prediction disagrees with the actual resolved next PC. This\\nshould recover most repeated loop-branch and unconditional jump penalties after\\nwarm-up with lower Fmax risk than the failed static predictor.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted next-PC and prediction-valid metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Implement a small direct-mapped BTB/BHT lookup in IF, select stored targets on confident tag hits, and update entries from EX resolution signals.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Latch IF prediction metadata into ID/EX without changing raw instruction rs fields or RVFI-visible...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Source-aware load-use interlock\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard compares the prior load destination against both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction. For many RV32I encodings one or both fields are not architecturally read, so the core can inject a one-cycle bubble after loads even when there is no true dependency. CoreMark has dense load, immediate, address-update, and control sequences, so eliminating false bubbles should improve iterations per cycle with very small RTL cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard compares the prior load destination against both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction. For many RV32I encodings one or both fields are not architecturally read, so the core can inject a one-cycle bubble after loads even when there is no true dependency. CoreMark has dense load, immediate, address-update, and control sequences, so eliminating false bubbles should improve iterations per cycle with very small RTL cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add compact IF/ID source-use predicates and gate the existing load-use comparison with them. Instructions that only read rs1, only read rs2, or read no integer source should not stall just because an immediate or destination bitfield happens to equal the load rd. The implementation must leave the raw instruction rs bitfields and regfile-read values unchanged through the pipeline so RVFI and cosim still see the same architectural source metadata; only the interlock predicate changes.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add IF/ID rs1_used and rs2_used inputs and apply them to the load-use dependency comparisons without changing other stall, flush, or hold priorities.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive compact source-use predicates from the IF/ID instruction opcode/funct class and...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Register the IF/ID boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID register: io_imemData feeds decode, immediate generation, regfile address selection, hazard inputs, and the ID/EX register in the same cycle. That structure keeps CPI low but likely puts external instruction-memory output, decoder fanout, and regfile read timing on one FPGA-critical path. Prior fetch-ahead structures lost badly because queue control and prediction logic made the front end more complex; a single registered IF/ID boundary is the minimal structural retiming that targets the same timing path without adding speculation or buffering policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID register: io_imemData feeds decode, immediate generation, regfile address selection, hazard inputs, and the ID/EX register in the same cycle. That structure keeps CPI low but likely puts external instruction-memory output, decoder fanout, and regfile read timing on one FPGA-critical path. Prior fetch-ahead structures lost badly because queue control and prediction logic made the front end more complex; a single registered IF/ID boundary is the minimal structural retiming that targets the same timing path without adding speculation or buffering policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert if_stage from a combinational IF/ID payload producer into a simple one-entry registered fetch/decode boundary. The PC still advances sequentially when the front end is not stalled, redirects still override stalls and flush the younger instruction, and ID consumes the registered instruction exactly as today. This should break the imem_data-to-decoder-to-ID/EX critical path and improve Fmax while preserving single-issue throughput; the expected CPI cost is limited to unchanged redirect/load-use behavior rather than the extra queue-control overhead seen in the failed skid-buffer attempt.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"ID-stage static control predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so CoreMark loop\\nbacks and direct jumps pay a two-instruction wrong-path flush. Prior IF-stage\\nstatic and BTB predictors showed that eliminating this penalty can help CPI,\\nbut putting immediate decode, target add, tag compare, or predictor RAM lookup\\non the fetch next-PC path costs too much Fmax on Tang Nano 20K.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so CoreMark loop\\nbacks and direct jumps pay a two-instruction wrong-path flush. Prior IF-stage\\nstatic and BTB predictors showed that eliminating this penalty can help CPI,\\nbut putting immediate decode, target add, tag compare, or predictor RAM lookup\\non the fetch next-PC path costs too much Fmax on Tang Nano 20K.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the lightweight static predictor out of IF and into ID. IF should remain\\na simple sequential pc+4 fetch unless an existing redirect arrives, while ID\\ndecodes the fetched instruction and redirects one stage early for aligned JAL\\nand aligned backward conditional branches. Carry the ID-predicted next PC into\\nEX so the branch/jump resolver redirects only when the actual next PC differs\\nfrom the prediction. This keeps predictor work off the front-end critical path\\nand still saves one of the two taken-control-flow bubbles in CoreMark loops.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an ID/EX predicted-next-PC field so EX can compare the static ID prediction with the actual resolved next PC.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ID-stage prediction redirect signals to IF and route the carried predicted next PC into EX resolution.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept an ID-stage prediction redirect with lower priority than EX correctio...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Case-based MEM byte-lane muxes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already gained by removing rare DIV/REM from the common\\nEX datapath, while recent front-end and multiplier micro-optimizations lost\\nFmax. A lower-risk remaining hot path is the MEM/WB load-data and store-mask\\nlogic: CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the current MEM stage uses variable\\nshifts for byte extraction and byte-lane mask generation in the same cycle\\nthat load data can feed writeback and forwarding.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already gained by removing rare DIV/REM from the common\\nEX datapath, while recent front-end and multiplier micro-optimizations lost\\nFmax. A lower-risk remaining hot path is the MEM/WB load-data and store-mask\\nlogic: CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the current MEM stage uses variable\\nshifts for byte extraction and byte-lane mask generation in the same cycle\\nthat load data can feed writeback and forwarding.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the MEM-stage variable shifts with explicit case muxes indexed by\\naddress bits. Generate byte and halfword load slices directly from\\ndmem_rdata[7:0], [15:8], [23:16], and [31:24], and generate store masks from\\nwidth/address case arms rather than left-shifting a constant. This should map\\nto smaller LUT mux trees on Tang Nano 20K, shorten the dmem_rdata-to-WB and\\naddress-to-mask paths, and preserve the exact RVFI aligned-memory reporting,\\nmisalignment traps, and pipeline timing.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite byte/halfword load extraction and store byte-mask generation as explicit case muxes instead of variable shifts, leaving misalignment gating and RVFI fields unchanged.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite byte/halfword lo...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Iterative high-half multiply side unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The successful DIV/REM side-unit hypothesis showed that this FPGA benefits\\nwhen rare, wide arithmetic is removed from the common EX-stage ALU result\\npath. The current ALU still computes three 64-bit multiply variants every\\ncycle and muxes their high halves alongside the common RV32I and low-half\\nMUL operations. CoreMark should mostly exercise ordinary integer ops and\\nlow-half MUL, while MULH/MULHU/MULHSU are uncommon in compiler output.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The successful DIV/REM side-unit hypothesis showed that this FPGA benefits\\nwhen rare, wide arithmetic is removed from the common EX-stage ALU result\\npath. The current ALU still computes three 64-bit multiply variants every\\ncycle and muxes their high halves alongside the common RV32I and low-half\\nMUL operations. CoreMark should mostly exercise ordinary integer ops and\\nlow-half MUL, while MULH/MULHU/MULHSU are uncommon in compiler output.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as a single-cycle low-half multiply, but move ALU_MULH,\\nALU_MULHU, and ALU_MULHSU into a small multi-cycle high-multiply side unit\\nowned by EX, using the same stall/consume pattern already proven for DIV/REM.\\nThe common ALU path then only needs the low-half unsigned product for MUL and\\nno longer carries signed high-product result muxing on every instruction.\\nRare high-half multiply instructions pay a short structural stall, but the\\nexpected CoreMark mix should recover more Fmax than it loses in IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real ALU_MULH, ALU_MULHU, and ALU_MULHSU product logic from the normal combinational ALU path while preserving RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect high-half multiply operations, start a small side unit, stall EX until the r...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Single-entry loop target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The failed predictor attempts show that broad prediction logic loses when it adds immediate decode, target adders, RAM lookup, counters, or same-cycle ID redirect control to the front-end critical path. CoreMark still has repeated loop-back branches that pay the current EX-resolution flush penalty, so the best remaining predictor angle is a much narrower mechanism that only learns the last hot backward branch target and keeps all target computation in EX.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The failed predictor attempts show that broad prediction logic loses when it adds immediate decode, target adders, RAM lookup, counters, or same-cycle ID redirect control to the front-end critical path. CoreMark still has repeated loop-back branches that pay the current EX-resolution flush penalty, so the best remaining predictor angle is a much narrower mechanism that only learns the last hot backward branch target and keeps all target computation in EX.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry last-taken backward-branch predictor updated from resolved EX-stage branches. IF predicts taken only when the current PC exactly matches the stored branch PC, using the already-registered target from the entry; all other fetches stay simple pc+4, and no instruction immediate decode or branch target addition occurs in IF. Carry the predicted next PC through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX redirects only when the actual resolved next PC differs, correcting loop exits and cold misses while eliminating most repeat loop-back bubbles with far less timing cost than the prior static and BTB predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can distinguish correct loop predictions from loop-exit mispredicts.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"descri...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Drop regfile bulk reset\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current core still synchronously clears all 32 integer registers on reset.\\nThat adds reset fanout and reset muxing across roughly a thousand register-file\\nbits, even though RV32I does not architecturally require x1-x31 to reset to\\nzero and benchmark software initializes the registers it depends on. Prior\\nmicro-opt attempts that touched fetch prediction or multiplier structure paid\\ncontrol/datapath costs, so a contained timing cleanup with no CPI effect is a\\nbetter fit for the next slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core still synchronously clears all 32 integer registers on reset.\\nThat adds reset fanout and reset muxing across roughly a thousand register-file\\nbits, even though RV32I does not architecturally require x1-x31 to reset to\\nzero and benchmark software initializes the registers it depends on. Prior\\nmicro-opt attempts that touched fetch prediction or multiplier structure paid\\ncontrol/datapath costs, so a contained timing cleanup with no CPI effect is a\\nbetter fit for the next slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the bulk reset loop from the integer register file while preserving x0\\nhardwiring, normal synchronous writes, and the same-cycle write-first read\\nbypass. This should reduce reset-net fanout and per-bit reset control in a hot\\nalways-on structure, giving nextpnr more freedom to place the regfile and its\\nbypass muxes. CoreMark CPI should be unchanged because the pipeline behavior,\\nforwarding, RVFI retirement, and writeback timing are identical after reset.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the synchronous reset clearing loop for x1-x31, keep x0 reads forced to zero, and preserve the write-first bypass and write gating semantics.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{...\n  Line 15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Selective store stall bypass\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes globally whenever a STORE reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. In the tournament CoreMark mode the data port has random backpressure, so store stalls unnecessarily block later independent ALU, branch, and multiply work even though the store payload is already fully known at MEM. Prior front-end decoupling attempts regressed because they added timing-critical fetch control; a back-end-only decoupling point should target IPC under dStall with less fetch-path risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes globally whenever a STORE reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. In the tournament CoreMark mode the data port has random backpressure, so store stalls unnecessarily block later independent ALU, branch, and multiply work even though the store payload is already fully known at MEM. Prior front-end decoupling attempts regressed because they added timing-critical fetch control; a back-end-only decoupling point should target IPC under dStall with less fetch-path risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry store buffer at the MEM boundary for aligned, non-MMIO stores. When a normal store reaches MEM and dmem is not ready, capture its address, replicated write data, and byte mask, allow the store to retire through MEM/WB, and keep driving the buffered write until the bus accepts it. While the buffer is occupied, stall only younger LOAD/STORE instructions to preserve memory ordering and the single dmem port; let younger non-memory instructions continue. Do not buffer UART or timing-marker MMIO stores so CoreMark brackets and output ordering remain exact. This should hide a fraction of random store backpressure cycles without changing nret, branch behavior, or common EX timing.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a one...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny JALR return target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictor attempts lost fitness because they put immediate decode,\\ntarget addition, BTB lookup, or loop-PC compare control on the front-end timing\\npath. CoreMark still pays the existing EX-resolution flush on direct calls,\\nindirect returns, and other taken JALR instructions, and return targets are often\\nstable for a given return instruction PC in this small benchmark binary.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictor attempts lost fitness because they put immediate decode,\\ntarget addition, BTB lookup, or loop-PC compare control on the front-end timing\\npath. CoreMark still pays the existing EX-resolution flush on direct calls,\\nindirect returns, and other taken JALR instructions, and return targets are often\\nstable for a given return instruction PC in this small benchmark binary.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a very narrow return-target predictor updated only from resolved EX-stage\\nJALR return-like instructions, such as JALR x0, x1/x5, 0. Keep target computation\\nin EX and store the resolved return instruction PC plus actual target in a tiny\\none-entry or two-entry table. IF remains mostly sequential and predicts only on\\nan exact registered PC hit, using the stored target with no instruction decode,\\nimmediate generation, or target add in the fetch path. Carry the predicted next\\nPC through ID/EX so EX corrects stale entries and non-return JALR cases. This\\ntargets a different CoreMark control-flow penalty than the failed loop predictors\\nwhile keeping the predictor small enough to have a plausible Fmax/IPC tradeoff.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX so EX can validate return-target predictions without changing RVFI retirement fields.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Ad...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Prune late pipeline control fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent attempts show that adding front-end prediction or arithmetic side-control tends to cost more Fmax than it saves, while the successful MEM-stage case-mux change improved fitness by simplifying always-active datapaths. The current pipeline still carries the full decoded ctrl_t through EX/MEM and MEM/WB even though many fields are dead after EX, and almost all fields are dead after MEM. Those unnecessary bits add flops, reset/hold muxing, struct routing, and fanout on hot writeback and forwarding control.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent attempts show that adding front-end prediction or arithmetic side-control tends to cost more Fmax than it saves, while the successful MEM-stage case-mux change improved fitness by simplifying always-active datapaths. The current pipeline still carries the full decoded ctrl_t through EX/MEM and MEM/WB even though many fields are dead after EX, and almost all fields are dead after MEM. Those unnecessary bits add flops, reset/hold muxing, struct routing, and fanout on hot writeback and forwarding control.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the late pipeline control payload into narrower MEM-stage and WB-stage control structs. EX/MEM only needs memory access width/sign, mem read/write, reg_write, mem_to_reg, and trap state; MEM/WB only needs reg_write, mem_to_reg, and trap state because RVFI memory masks/data have already been materialized. Removing unused branch, jump, ALU-op, operand-select, AUIPC/LUI, and memory-format bits from late pipeline registers should reduce Tang Nano 20K placement/routing pressure and shorten small but always-active control muxes without changing instruction timing, RVFI fields, or CoreMark CPI.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add narrow ex_mem and mem_wb control typedefs, change ex_mem_t and m...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"MEM load-data bypass to EX\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always injects a bubble for a load-use pair,\\neven when the data memory is ready and the load data is available during the\\nfollowing MEM cycle. CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the recent MEM-stage\\nbyte-lane improvement indicates this benchmark is sensitive to the memory\\ndatapath. Prior structural frontend decoupling and prediction attempts paid\\ntoo much fetch-path timing cost, so a backend bypass is a more focused IPC\\nimprovement.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always injects a bubble for a load-use pair,\\neven when the data memory is ready and the load data is available during the\\nfollowing MEM cycle. CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the recent MEM-stage\\nbyte-lane improvement indicates this benchmark is sensitive to the memory\\ndatapath. Prior structural frontend decoupling and prediction attempts paid\\ntoo much fetch-path timing cost, so a backend bypass is a more focused IPC\\nimprovement.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a direct MEM-stage load-result bypass into the EX operand forwarding\\nnetwork. When a load sits in EX/MEM and a younger instruction in ID/EX reads\\nthe same rd, EX should use the current MEM load_data instead of stalling for\\nthe value to reach MEM/WB. The bypass must be disabled for misaligned/trapping\\nloads so dependent instructions retain the old architectural register value,\\nand dmem backpressure should still freeze the pipeline until valid load data\\nis available. This removes the normal one-cycle load-use penalty without\\nadding branch prediction, fetch queues, or nret changes.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the combinational aligned load_data value and a bypass-valid signal gated off for misaligned or trapping loads.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"descripti...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Lookahead hot-branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost because the prediction decision sat directly on the current IF next-PC path: immediate decode, target adders, tag compares, or same-cycle ID redirects reduced Fmax more than CoreMark gained from fewer taken-branch bubbles. CoreMark still has hot loop-back branches, so the remaining promising predictor angle is to keep prediction state registered and move the lookup one cycle ahead of the branch fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost because the prediction decision sat directly on the current IF next-PC path: immediate decode, target adders, tag compares, or same-cycle ID redirects reduced Fmax more than CoreMark gained from fewer taken-branch bubbles. CoreMark still has hot loop-back branches, so the remaining promising predictor angle is to keep prediction state registered and move the lookup one cycle ahead of the branch fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry hot control-flow predictor that is updated from EX with the resolved PC and target of taken backward branches and direct jumps, but consume it through a one-cycle sequential lookahead. While fetching PC N, compare the registered predictor PC against N+4 and latch a prearmed prediction for the next sequential fetch; when PC N+4 is fetched on the following cycle, the IF next-PC mux uses only the registered prearmed target, not a same-cycle tag compare or target adder. Carry the predicted next PC with the instruction so EX redirects only on a real mismatch. This should recover loop-back taken-branch bubbles while avoiding the timing pattern that broke the prior IF BTB, static, loop, and return predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can validate a prearmed prediction without c...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Drop dead branch payload\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent micro-optimization attempts show that added front-end logic, broad\\ncontrol repacking, and multiplier restructuring tend to lose Fmax, while\\ntargeted removal or simplification of always-carried datapath logic is the\\nsafer path. In the current bench core, branch resolution is fully completed\\ninside EX: redirect, predictor update, pc_next, and trap handling are all\\nproduced before the EX/MEM register. The EX/MEM payload still carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target even though MEM, WB, RVFI, forwarding, and\\nhazard logic do not consume them.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent micro-optimization attempts show that added front-end logic, broad\\ncontrol repacking, and multiplier restructuring tend to lose Fmax, while\\ntargeted removal or simplification of always-carried datapath logic is the\\nsafer path. In the current bench core, branch resolution is fully completed\\ninside EX: redirect, predictor update, pc_next, and trap handling are all\\nproduced before the EX/MEM register. The EX/MEM payload still carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target even though MEM, WB, RVFI, forwarding, and\\nhazard logic do not consume them.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t and\\ndelete the corresponding EX-stage register assignments. This should reduce\\nthe EX/MEM register by 33 bits, including reset and dmem-stall hold muxing,\\nwithout changing instruction timing, branch redirect behavior, predictor\\nupdates, RVFI pc_wdata, trap behavior, or CoreMark CPI. The change is much\\nnarrower than the prior late-control pruning attempt: it only deletes fields\\nalready proven dead downstream, avoiding new packed-control structs or extra\\nmuxing on hot paths.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the unused branch_taken and branc...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Precompute MEM access descriptor in EX\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest recent non-predictor gain came from simplifying MEM-stage byte-lane muxing, which suggests the load/store formatting path is still important for Tang Nano 20K fitness. The current MEM stage still derives misalignment, byte masks, replicated store data, aligned RVFI addresses, and dmem enables in the same cycle that dmem_rdata is selected and forwarded to writeback. Front-end queues, IF retiming, high-multiply side units, and direct load-data bypassing have already shown poor tradeoffs, so the next structural target should be a no-CPI retiming of an existing hot back-end path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest recent non-predictor gain came from simplifying MEM-stage byte-lane muxing, which suggests the load/store formatting path is still important for Tang Nano 20K fitness. The current MEM stage still derives misalignment, byte masks, replicated store data, aligned RVFI addresses, and dmem enables in the same cycle that dmem_rdata is selected and forwarded to writeback. Front-end queues, IF retiming, high-multiply side units, and direct load-data bypassing have already shown poor tradeoffs, so the next structural target should be a no-CPI retiming of an existing hot back-end path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the address-dependent memory access descriptor generation from MEM into EX, immediately after the effective address is computed. EX should precompute the byte mask, replicated store data, word-aligned RVFI address, memory-misalignment trap bit, and trap-gated control for load/store instructions, then carry those registered fields in EX/MEM. MEM can then drive dmem_wen/dmem_ren, RVFI masks, and store write data mostly from registered descriptor fields while retaining the existing load-data extraction from dmem_rdata. This should shorten the MEM address/control-to-writeback and dmem-enable paths with no CPI cost, while...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"Two-entry lookahead hot predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current one-entry lookahead predictor is the first predictor variant that improved fitness because it keeps the current IF next-PC mux free of tag comparisons and target adders. CoreMark still contains nested loops and direct control-flow edges, so a single learned PC can be evicted by another hot edge and lose most of the warm predictor benefit between repeated visits.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current one-entry lookahead predictor is the first predictor variant that improved fitness because it keeps the current IF next-PC mux free of tag comparisons and target adders. CoreMark still contains nested loops and direct control-flow edges, so a single learned PC can be evicted by another hot edge and lose most of the warm predictor benefit between repeated visits.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Expand the existing registered lookahead predictor in if_stage from one entry to two small entries, updated from the same EX-resolved taken backward branches and direct jumps. While fetching PC N, compare N+4 against both registered entry PCs only to prearm the following cycle; when the predicted instruction is actually fetched, the next-PC mux still consumes only the already-registered armed target. This should reduce predictor thrashing on nested CoreMark loops and call/jump structure without reintroducing the timing pattern that broke current-PC BTBs, static IF decode, ID redirects, or return predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the single pred_valid/pred_pc/pred_target entry with two registered entries, add simple replacement on EX updates, and prearm from a two-entry lookahead match while keeping the current next-PC mux driven only by armed_valid_q and armed_target_q.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"ch...\n  Line 23: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r8s0\", \"title\": \"Filter hot predictor JAL pollution\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core gained from a one-entry lookahead hot-branch predictor\\nbecause the fetch next-PC path consumes only registered prearmed state. The\\nremaining risk is that the single entry is updated by every direct JAL as\\nwell as hot backward loop branches, so forward calls in CoreMark can evict\\nthe loop-back edge that the predictor is best suited to accelerate.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core gained from a one-entry lookahead hot-branch predictor\\nbecause the fetch next-PC path consumes only registered prearmed state. The\\nremaining risk is that the single entry is updated by every direct JAL as\\nwell as hot backward loop branches, so forward calls in CoreMark can evict\\nthe loop-back edge that the predictor is best suited to accelerate.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Narrow the existing predictor update policy so the one-entry lookahead slot\\nlearns only taken backward control-flow edges, primarily conditional loop\\nbranches and any rare backward JALs, while ignoring forward direct-call JALs.\\nThis keeps the successful registered lookahead datapath intact, avoids the\\ntwo-entry predictor's added compare/replacement cost, and should improve\\nCoreMark iterations per cycle by keeping the single predictor entry focused\\non the hottest loop edge rather than call-site pollution.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change pred_update_valid so the hot lookahead predictor updates only for backward resolved targets, filtering forward JAL call targets while preserving EX correction and RVFI pc_next behavior.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Change pred_update_valid so the hot lookahead predictor updates only for backward resolved targets, filtering fo...\n  Line 24: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r8s1\", \"title\": \"Precompute PC-relative targets in ID\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already benefits from a registered lookahead hot-branch predictor, but EX still recomputes pc+4 and pc+imm for branches, JAL, AUIPC, link writeback, redirect targets, prediction correction, and RVFI pc_wdata. Prior IF-side prediction and buffering attempts regressed because they put extra compares, target adds, or queue control on the fetch PC path. A narrower structural retime can instead move PC-relative adders behind the existing ID/EX register and shorten the EX resolve/writeback muxing without changing speculation policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already benefits from a registered lookahead hot-branch predictor, but EX still recomputes pc+4 and pc+imm for branches, JAL, AUIPC, link writeback, redirect targets, prediction correction, and RVFI pc_wdata. Prior IF-side prediction and buffering attempts regressed because they put extra compares, target adds, or queue control on the fetch PC path. A narrower structural retime can instead move PC-relative adders behind the existing ID/EX register and shorten the EX resolve/writeback muxing without changing speculation policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add registered pc_plus4 and pc_plus_imm fields to the ID/EX payload, computed in id_stage from the fetched PC and decoded immediate. In ex_stage, use those registered values for branch targets, JAL targets, JAL/JALR link data, normal sequential pc_next, and AUIPC writeback, while keeping JALR's rs1+imm calculation in EX because it depends on forwarded rs1. This should reduce the always-active EX pc-add and branch/jump result mux depth while preserving the single-issue nret=1 RVFI contract, existing hot-branch predictor behavior, and all memory/divide stall rules.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Extend id_ex_t w...\n  Line 25: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r8s2\", \"title\": \"Loop-only lookahead training\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the one-entry sequential lookahead design because\\nit keeps tag comparison off the current IF next-PC mux. The failed two-entry\\nexpansion suggests the next predictor gain should not add more IF arming\\ncompares or replacement state. A simpler way to reduce one-entry thrash is to\\nstop training it with direct JAL targets that may be cold calls or one-shot\\ncontrol transfers and can evict the hot CoreMark loop-back branch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best predictor is the one-entry sequential lookahead design because\\nit keeps tag comparison off the current IF next-PC mux. The failed two-entry\\nexpansion suggests the next predictor gain should not add more IF arming\\ncompares or replacement state. A simpler way to reduce one-entry thrash is to\\nstop training it with direct JAL targets that may be cold calls or one-shot\\ncontrol transfers and can evict the hot CoreMark loop-back branch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Restrict the existing lookahead predictor update to taken backward conditional\\nbranches only, leaving the IF-side predictor entry, lookahead compare, armed\\ntarget mux, and carried predicted_pc_next metadata unchanged. This preserves\\nthe timing shape that improved fitness while making the single predictor entry\\nless prone to pollution from direct jumps. The tradeoff is giving up some JAL\\npredictions, but CoreMark's most valuable repeated control-flow edges should\\nbe loop branches, so the hotter entry should improve iterations per cycle with\\nlittle or no Fmax cost.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Narrow pred_update_valid so the one-entry lookahead predictor trains only on valid, legal, taken backward conditional branches instead of also replacing the entry with direct JAL targets.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fi...\n  Line 26: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r9s0\", \"title\": \"Trim halfword load muxes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The best successful micro-optimization so far simplified the MEM-stage\\nbyte-lane datapath by replacing variable shifts with explicit muxes. The\\ncurrent MEM stage still spends LUT depth on halfword byte lanes that are\\narchitecturally unreachable for legal LH/LHU/SH accesses: addr[0]=1 is a\\nmisalignment trap, dmem is gated off, reg_write is cleared, and the computed\\nhalfword value is not consumed. CoreMark uses aligned 16-bit matrix data, so\\nthe legal halfword fast path is worth keeping as small as possible.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The best successful micro-optimization so far simplified the MEM-stage\\nbyte-lane datapath by replacing variable shifts with explicit muxes. The\\ncurrent MEM stage still spends LUT depth on halfword byte lanes that are\\narchitecturally unreachable for legal LH/LHU/SH accesses: addr[0]=1 is a\\nmisalignment trap, dmem is gated off, reg_write is cleared, and the computed\\nhalfword value is not consumed. CoreMark uses aligned 16-bit matrix data, so\\nthe legal halfword fast path is worth keeping as small as possible.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Specialize the MEM-stage halfword path for aligned accesses. Generate\\nhalfword load data with a two-way addr[1] mux between dmem_rdata[15:0] and\\ndmem_rdata[31:16], and generate halfword write masks as addr[1] ? 4'b1100 :\\n4'b0011. Leave the existing misalignment detector, dmem gating, RVFI masks,\\ntrap propagation, and byte/word behavior unchanged. This should shorten the\\ndmem_rdata-to-WB path and address-to-mask path without adding pipeline\\ncontrol, frontend prediction logic, or EX-stage address precomputation.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace dead misaligned halfword load and mask case arms with aligned-only addr[1] muxes while preserving misalignment trap and RVFI gating semantics....\n  Line 27: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r9s1\", \"title\": \"Move all MUL ops to a side unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The successful DIV/REM side unit showed that this core benefits when rare or\\nheavy RV32M arithmetic is removed from the always-active EX ALU result path.\\nA later high-half-multiply side unit regressed because low-half MUL still left\\na 32x32 multiplier in the common ALU mux, so the structural timing bottleneck\\nwas not actually removed while new stall control was added.\\n\\nThe remaining untried structural split is to move the entire MUL family,\\nincluding ALU_MUL, out of alu.sv. CoreMark will pay extra cycles on multiply\\ninstructions, but the normal integer, branch, load/store, and predictor paths\\nshould lose the parallel signed/unsigned multiplier fanout and wide M-result\\nmuxing that currently sit in the EX stage.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The successful DIV/REM side unit showed that this core benefits when rare or\\nheavy RV32M arithmetic is removed from the always-active EX ALU result path.\\nA later high-half-multiply side unit regressed because low-half MUL still left\\na 32x32 multiplier in the common ALU mux, so the structural timing bottleneck\\nwas not actually removed while new stall control was added.\\n\\nThe remaining untried structural split is to move the entire MUL family,\\nincluding ALU_MUL, out of alu.sv. CoreMark will pay extra cycles on multiply\\ninstructions, but the normal integer, branch, load/store, and predictor paths\\nshould lose the parallel signed/unsigned multiplier fanout and wide M-result\\nmuxing that currently sit in the EX stage.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a dedicated multi-cycle multiply side unit for MUL, MULH, MULHU, and\\nMULHSU, using the same start/wait/consume pattern as the existing DIV/REM\\nunit. In normal builds, alu.sv should no longer implement real multiply\\ndatapaths; EX detects multiply opcodes, starts the side unit, emits bubbles\\nwhile the result is pending, and writes the side-unit result into EX/ME...\n  Line 28: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r9s2\", \"title\": \"Promote repeated lookahead targets\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The one-entry registered lookahead predictor is the only predictor variant that improved fitness because IF consumes only prearmed registered state. Later attempts regressed when they added a second IF compare/replacement path or filtered out direct JAL updates entirely, which suggests the entry needs better update selectivity without changing the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The one-entry registered lookahead predictor is the only predictor variant that improved fitness because IF consumes only prearmed registered state. Later attempts regressed when they added a second IF compare/replacement path or filtered out direct JAL updates entirely, which suggests the entry needs better update selectivity without changing the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep the existing active one-entry lookahead predictor and its single seq_pc compare, but add a non-fetch-path candidate entry used only by the EX update logic. A newly resolved taken backward branch or direct JAL first records as the candidate; it replaces the active predictor only when the same PC is seen again, while updates to the current active PC still refresh its target immediately. This should reduce eviction by one-shot calls and cold control-flow edges while still allowing repeated JALs and nested-loop branches to become predicted, avoiding both the failed two-entry IF lookup and the failed all-JAL filtering policies.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a candidate PC/target register pair to the existing lookahead predictor update path; promote candidates to the active entry only after a repeated resolved update while keeping the IF lookup as one active-entry seq_pc compare and one armed target mux.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"me...\n  Line 29: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r10s0\", \"title\": \"Use immediate sign for predictor update\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core depends on the one-entry registered lookahead predictor,\\nbut recent predictor variants regressed when they added IF-side compares,\\nreplacement state, or delayed promotion. A lower-risk micro-optimization is to\\nkeep the same single-entry predictor structure and useful direct-JAL training,\\nwhile trimming EX-stage predictor-update control that is not architecturally\\nvisible.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core depends on the one-entry registered lookahead predictor,\\nbut recent predictor variants regressed when they added IF-side compares,\\nreplacement state, or delayed promotion. A lower-risk micro-optimization is to\\nkeep the same single-entry predictor structure and useful direct-JAL training,\\nwhile trimming EX-stage predictor-update control that is not architecturally\\nvisible.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"For conditional branches, replace the predictor update test\\n`branch_target < in.pc` with the sign bit of the decoded B-immediate. On the\\nbounded CoreMark address range, a negative B-immediate is exactly the loop-back\\ncase the predictor is trying to learn, and any rare wraparound distinction only\\naffects speculative next-PC choice that EX already corrects. This removes a\\n32-bit less-than comparator from the always-active EX predictor-update cone,\\npreserves direct JAL updates that prior results showed are useful, and should\\nimprove Fmax without changing CPI on correctly predicted hot loops.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace branch_target < in.pc in pred_update_valid with the branch immediate sign bit, while leaving direct JAL updates, redirect correction, RVFI pc_next, and trap behavior unchanged.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/e...\n  Line 30: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\", \"title\": \"Store-drain buffer for dStall\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline globally freezes when a store reaches MEM while dmem is not ready, even though the store address, data, mask, and RVFI payload are already known. CoreMark runs with randomized data-memory backpressure, so store stalls can expose dead cycles that younger independent ALU and branch instructions could otherwise use. Prior structural front-end and arithmetic retiming attempts usually lost Fmax, so the most promising structural angle is a back-end decoupling point that leaves IF, prediction, decode, and the common EX ALU path unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline globally freezes when a store reaches MEM while dmem is not ready, even though the store address, data, mask, and RVFI payload are already known. CoreMark runs with randomized data-memory backpressure, so store stalls can expose dead cycles that younger independent ALU and branch instructions could otherwise use. Prior structural front-end and arithmetic retiming attempts usually lost Fmax, so the most promising structural angle is a back-end decoupling point that leaves IF, prediction, decode, and the common EX ALU path unchanged.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry store-drain buffer after MEM for aligned, non-MMIO stores. When such a store cannot be accepted by dmem, capture its addr/wdata/wmask, allow the store to advance to MEM/WB and retire once, and keep driving the buffered write until io_dmemReady accepts it. While the buffer is pending, stall younger LOAD/STORE instructions and any MMIO/timing-marker store, but allow younger non-memory instructions to pass through MEM so random store backpressure is partly hidden without changing nret or RVFI order. This is a refined version of the earlier broken store-buffer idea: keep memory ordering conservative, do not buffer UART or CoreMark marker writes, and do not add load forwarding from the buff...\n  Line 31: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r10s2\", \"title\": \"Directionless hot-edge training\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current one-entry registered lookahead predictor is the only predictor variant\\nthat improved fitness because it keeps tag comparison off the current IF next-PC\\nmux. Later predictor regressions came from adding IF lookup complexity or delaying\\nuseful updates. A narrower update-policy change can try to recover more CoreMark\\ncontrol-flow bubbles while preserving the successful IF timing shape.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current one-entry registered lookahead predictor is the only predictor variant\\nthat improved fitness because it keeps tag comparison off the current IF next-PC\\nmux. Later predictor regressions came from adding IF lookup complexity or delaying\\nuseful updates. A narrower update-policy change can try to recover more CoreMark\\ncontrol-flow bubbles while preserving the successful IF timing shape.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Train the existing one-entry lookahead predictor on every resolved taken\\nconditional branch, not only taken backward branches, while continuing to train on\\ndirect JALs and still excluding JALR. This removes the branch_target < pc direction\\nfilter from the EX update path and lets the same registered prearmed target\\nmechanism learn hot forward taken branches in CoreMark. Correctness is unchanged\\nbecause EX already carries predicted_pc_next and redirects on any mismatch, so\\nbiased branches that later fall through are repaired exactly like loop exits.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Broaden pred_update_valid so the existing one-entry lookahead predictor trains on all legal taken conditional branches plus direct JALs, removing the backward-target direction check without adding IF-stage lookup logic.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"de...","metadata":{"matches":31,"truncated":false},"title":"micro_opt|micro-opt|ALU|forward|regfile|decode|hazard|mask|load|MUL|DIV|critical|Fmax","time":{"start":1778651541040,"end":1778651541053}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06a33425d8edd2ba016a041194dd04819aac158a115924d821"}},"id":"prt_e1fe4ae2d001nenzd9cONqjUwn","sessionID":"ses_1e01b7558ffey1JQ9pYmA0GhMu","messageID":"msg_e1fe48b0a001lZTRXPZPl7FsDi"}}
