{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778651662863,"sessionID":"ses_1e01b7558ffey1JQ9pYmA0GhMu","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_zllbuIhSxBwi65i65EJZ4eP9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r11s0\n+title: \"Explicit signed compare datapath\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core already gained from simplifying the MEM byte-lane datapath, while most attempts that added predictor state, new side units, or broad control repacking regressed. A remaining low-risk hot cone is signed comparison in EX: SLT and BLT/BGE currently rely on generic signed less-than operators, which can infer full-width comparator/subtractor logic on the ALU and branch-resolution paths.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Replace generic signed less-than comparisons with an explicit sign-bit fast path in both the ALU and branch comparator. For signed compares, when operand signs differ the result is just the left operand sign; when signs match, compare the low 31 bits as unsigned. This preserves exact RV32I SLT/BLT/BGE semantics, keeps the pipeline and predictor behavior unchanged, and may map to shallower LUT/carry logic on Tang Nano 20K for CoreMark's compare-heavy control flow.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/alu.sv\n+    description: \"Implement ALU_SLT with explicit sign-bit handling and an unsigned low-bit compare instead of a generic signed less-than operator.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Share the same explicit signed-less-than predicate for BLT/BGE branch resolution while leaving unsigned/equality branches and redirect semantics unchanged.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r11s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.cla