{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778652375763,"sessionID":"ses_1e00f9204ffeW3o4DkhsfmWwhG","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_DiQlLBV44B1rDSov0Ylgtds6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r12s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r12s0\n+title: \"Suppress load EX forwarding\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior micro-opt results show that this core rewards small removals from always-active datapaths, while broader control repacking and comparator rewrites tend to perturb timing badly. The EX operand forwarding unit still treats a load in EX/MEM as a normal producer even though its architectural rd value is not available until MEM/WB and the existing load-use interlock already prevents a dependent instruction from consuming EX/MEM load data.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Gate the EX/MEM forwarding candidate so it is only eligible for non-load register writers. Loads should continue to stall true one-cycle consumers and then forward through MEM/WB, while ALU, jump-link, AUIPC, LUI, and multiply results keep the existing EX/MEM bypass. This removes a false high-priority bypass case, reduces unnecessary compare/select pressure in the EX operand mux control, and avoids ever selecting a load effective address as forwarded rd data under unusual stall timing, without changing CPI or the RVFI retirement contract.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Drive the forward unit's EX/MEM write-enable input with a non-load producer predicate, leaving MEM/WB forwarding and hazard priorities unchanged.\"\n+  - file: rtl/forward_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Document or rename the EX/MEM forwarding input as a bypass-eligible producer so loads are excluded from the high-priority EX/MEM path without changing the two-bit select encoding.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the follo