{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778645025408,"sessionID":"ses_1e07ff9a7ffejB7zZWK7wlGy0D","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_oZOolw3kojcfadoFZrOnQU1H","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\n+title: \"Drop regfile bulk reset\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current core still synchronously clears all 32 integer registers on reset.\n+  That adds reset fanout and reset muxing across roughly a thousand register-file\n+  bits, even though RV32I does not architecturally require x1-x31 to reset to\n+  zero and benchmark software initializes the registers it depends on. Prior\n+  micro-opt attempts that touched fetch prediction or multiplier structure paid\n+  control/datapath costs, so a contained timing cleanup with no CPI effect is a\n+  better fit for the next slot.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Remove the bulk reset loop from the integer register file while preserving x0\n+  hardwiring, normal synchronous writes, and the same-cycle write-first read\n+  bypass. This should reduce reset-net fanout and per-bit reset control in a hot\n+  always-on structure, giving nextpnr more freedom to place the regfile and its\n+  bypass muxes. CoreMark CPI should be unchanged because the pipeline behavior,\n+  forwarding, RVFI retirement, and writeback timing are identical after reset.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/reg_file.sv\n+    description: \"Remove the synchronous reset clearing loop for x1-x31, keep x0 reads forced to zero, and preserve the write-first bypass and write gating semantics.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r5s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypothes