{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778647816308,"sessionID":"ses_1e05537c6ffeK5YrrJ77OZbTce","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_1coICBg3v0UR7goVPIN42TYb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r8s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r8s0\n+title: \"Filter hot predictor JAL pollution\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The current best core gained from a one-entry lookahead hot-branch predictor\n+  because the fetch next-PC path consumes only registered prearmed state. The\n+  remaining risk is that the single entry is updated by every direct JAL as\n+  well as hot backward loop branches, so forward calls in CoreMark can evict\n+  the loop-back edge that the predictor is best suited to accelerate.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Narrow the existing predictor update policy so the one-entry lookahead slot\n+  learns only taken backward control-flow edges, primarily conditional loop\n+  branches and any rare backward JALs, while ignoring forward direct-call JALs.\n+  This keeps the successful registered lookahead datapath intact, avoids the\n+  two-entry predictor's added compare/replacement cost, and should improve\n+  CoreMark iterations per cycle by keeping the single predictor entry focused\n+  on the hottest loop edge rather than call-site pollution.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Change pred_update_valid so the hot lookahead predictor updates only for backward resolved targets, filtering forward JAL call targets while preserving EX correction and RVFI pc_next behavior.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r8s0.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r8s0.yaml\