{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778648712873,"sessionID":"ses_1e04748efffeMkGOB3l77gALaA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_RXz9qzBEwANYedzMecv2QLDz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r9s0.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-001-r9s0\n+title: \"Trim halfword load muxes\"\n+category: micro_opt\n+motivation: |\n+  The best successful micro-optimization so far simplified the MEM-stage\n+  byte-lane datapath by replacing variable shifts with explicit muxes. The\n+  current MEM stage still spends LUT depth on halfword byte lanes that are\n+  architecturally unreachable for legal LH/LHU/SH accesses: addr[0]=1 is a\n+  misalignment trap, dmem is gated off, reg_write is cleared, and the computed\n+  halfword value is not consumed. CoreMark uses aligned 16-bit matrix data, so\n+  the legal halfword fast path is worth keeping as small as possible.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Specialize the MEM-stage halfword path for aligned accesses. Generate\n+  halfword load data with a two-way addr[1] mux between dmem_rdata[15:0] and\n+  dmem_rdata[31:16], and generate halfword write masks as addr[1] ? 4'b1100 :\n+  4'b0011. Leave the existing misalignment detector, dmem gating, RVFI masks,\n+  trap propagation, and byte/word behavior unchanged. This should shorten the\n+  dmem_rdata-to-WB path and address-to-mask path without adding pipeline\n+  control, frontend prediction logic, or EX-stage address precomputation.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace dead misaligned halfword load and mask case arms with aligned-only addr[1] muxes while preserving misalignment trap and RVFI gating semantics.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513