{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778650233945,"sessionID":"ses_1e0305f9cffej9ukbpSH4ImNgU","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_EVWs0ikDUi3TDL4tTSO3ndCn","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\n+title: Store-drain buffer for dStall\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline globally freezes when a store reaches MEM while dmem is not ready, even though the store address, data, mask, and RVFI payload are already known. CoreMark runs with randomized data-memory backpressure, so store stalls can expose dead cycles that younger independent ALU and branch instructions could otherwise use. Prior structural front-end and arithmetic retiming attempts usually lost Fmax, so the most promising structural angle is a back-end decoupling point that leaves IF, prediction, decode, and the common EX ALU path unchanged.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry store-drain buffer after MEM for aligned, non-MMIO stores. When such a store cannot be accepted by dmem, capture its addr/wdata/wmask, allow the store to advance to MEM/WB and retire once, and keep driving the buffered write until io_dmemReady accepts it. While the buffer is pending, stall younger LOAD/STORE instructions and any MMIO/timing-marker store, but allow younger non-memory instructions to pass through MEM so random store backpressure is partly hidden without changing nret or RVFI order. This is a refined version of the earlier broken store-buffer idea: keep memory ordering conservative, do not buffer UART or CoreMark marker writes, and do not add load forwarding from the buffer.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: Add a one-entry non-MMIO store-drain buffer, mux dmem outputs between the pending buffered store and the current MEM operation, and retire buffered stores exactly once through the existing MEM/WB path.\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: Add a store-buffer block signal so younger memory operations and MMIO marker writes stall while a buffered store is pending, while younger non-memory instructions can continue.\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: Wire store-buffer pending/block status between MEM and hazard control without changing the nret=1 RVFI port set or existing predictor interfaces.\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r10s1\n+title: Store-drain buffer for dStall\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline globally freezes when a store reaches MEM while dmem is not ready, even though the store address, data, mask, and RVFI payload are already known. CoreMark runs with randomized data-memory backpressure, so store stalls can expose dead cycles that younger independent ALU and branch instructions could otherwise use. Prior structural front-end and arithmetic retiming attempts usually lost Fmax, so the most promising structural angle is a back-end decoupling point that leaves IF, prediction, decode, and the common EX ALU path unchanged.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry store-drain buffer after MEM for aligned, non-MMIO stores. When such a store cannot be accepted by dmem, capture its addr/wdata/wmask, allow the store to advance to MEM/WB and retire once, and keep driving the buffered write until io_dmemReady accepts it. While the buffer is pending, stall younger LOAD/STORE instructions and any MMIO/timing-marker store, but allow younger non-memory instructions to pass through MEM so random store backpressure is partly hidden without changing nret or RVFI order. This is a refined version of the earlier broken store-buffer idea: keep memory ordering conservative, do not buffer UART or CoreMark marker writes, and do not add load forwarding from the buffer.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 4\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: Add a one-entry non-MMIO store-drain buffer, mux dmem outputs between the pending buffered store and the current MEM operation, and retire buffered stores exactly once through the existing MEM/WB path.\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: Add a store-buffer block signal so younger memory operations and MMIO marker writes stall while a buffered store is pending, while younger non-memory instructions can continue.\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: Wire store-buffer pending/block status between MEM and hazard control without changing the nret=1 RVFI port set or existing predictor interfaces.\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r10s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.cla