{"type":"text","timestamp":1778653691589,"sessionID":"ses_1dffbc90cffeEMgC4FgH8OAZ5u","part":{"id":"prt_e20057cf8001sjVah1bDj65O8C","messageID":"msg_e20050acc0013LolSpLeG6soHj","sessionID":"ses_1dffbc90cffeEMgC4FgH8OAZ5u","type":"text","text":"I’m writing the hypothesis YAML now. It proposes a one-entry fetch replay latch: capture an instruction response that arrives during a back-end stall, then consume it after the stall clears instead of depending on `io_imemReady` being high again.","time":{"start":1778653691128,"end":1778653691588},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0db530773e355094016a0419fb0974819bb5d7c4b485b81888","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778653699679,"sessionID":"ses_1dffbc90cffeEMgC4FgH8OAZ5u","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_zlg1K3jHdGBNTW2szdyP3f7l","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Fetch replay latch\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end discards an instruction-memory response whenever the back end is stalled by dmem or DIV/REM, because the PC is held and the IF/ID payload is not a registered valid-ready boundary. In the randomized CoreMark mode, this means an instruction that was available during a back-end stall may need to be refetched and can then be delayed by a later independent imem stall. Prior fetch queues regressed because they advanced PC and added queue control; a one-entry replay latch only captures the current PC response and should be much smaller.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry fetch replay latch in if_stage that records pc, predicted_pc_next, and instr when the pipeline is stalled behind IF but io_imemReady is high. When the back-end stall clears, ID consumes the latched instruction even if io_imemReady is low that cycle, and the PC advances exactly once; redirects and flushes invalidate the latch. This structurally overlaps random instruction-memory availability with dmem/div stalls without adding fetch-ahead policy, branch predictor entries, memory reordering, or nret changes, so it should recover some CoreMark iterations per cycle with less Fmax risk than the failed two-entry skid buffer.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry replay latch for the current PC's fetched instruction, consume it before live imem data, and invalidate it on redirect/reset/flush.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Replace raw imem_ready front-end blocking with an effective fetch-available signal so a replayed instruction can advance while a live imem response is stalled.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire io_imemReady into if_stage replay capture and route the IF fetch-available/consume signal into hazard control without changing the nret=1 RVFI port shape.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Fetch replay latch\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end discards an instruction-memory response whenever the back end is stalled by dmem or DIV/REM, because the PC is held and the IF/ID payload is not a registered valid-ready boundary. In the randomized CoreMark mode, this means an instruction that was available during a back-end stall may need to be refetched and can then be delayed by a later independent imem stall. Prior fetch queues regressed because they advanced PC and added queue control; a one-entry replay latch only captures the current PC response and should be much smaller.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry fetch replay latch in if_stage that records pc, predicted_pc_next, and instr when the pipeline is stalled behind IF but io_imemReady is high. When the back-end stall clears, ID consumes the latched instruction even if io_imemReady is low that cycle, and the PC advances exactly once; redirects and flushes invalidate the latch. This structurally overlaps random instruction-memory availability with dmem/div stalls without adding fetch-ahead policy, branch predictor entries, memory reordering, or nret changes, so it should recover some CoreMark iterations per cycle with less Fmax risk than the failed two-entry skid buffer.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry replay latch for the current PC's fetched instruction, consume it before live imem data, and invalidate it on redirect/reset/flush.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Replace raw imem_ready front-end blocking with an effective fetch-available signal so a replayed instruction can advance while a live imem response is stalled.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire io_imemReady into if_stage replay capture and route the IF fetch-available/consume signal into hazard control without changing the nret=1 RVFI port shape.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r13s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r13s1\n+title: \"Fetch replay latch\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end discards an instruction-memory response whenever the back end is stalled by dmem or DIV/REM, because the PC is held and the IF/ID payload is not a registered valid-ready boundary. In the randomized CoreMark mode, this means an instruction that was available during a back-end stall may need to be refetched and can then be delayed by a later independent imem stall. Prior fetch queues regressed because they advanced PC and added queue control; a one-entry replay latch only captures the current PC response and should be much smaller.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry fetch replay latch in if_stage that records pc, predicted_pc_next, and instr when the pipeline is stalled behind IF but io_imemReady is high. When the back-end stall clears, ID consumes the latched instruction even if io_imemReady is low that cycle, and the PC advances exactly once; redirects and flushes invalidate the latch. This structurally overlaps random instruction-memory availability with dmem/div stalls without adding fetch-ahead policy, branch predictor entries, memory reordering, or nret changes, so it should recover some CoreMark iterations per cycle with less Fmax risk than the failed two-entry skid buffer.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry replay latch for the current PC's fetched instruction, consume it before live imem data, and invalidate it on redirect/reset/flush.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Replace raw imem_ready front-end blocking with an effective fetch-available signal so a replayed instruction can advance while a live imem response is stalled.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire io_imemReady into if_stage replay capture and route the IF fetch-available/consume signal into hazard control without changing the nret=1 RVFI port shape.\"\n","additions":17,"deletions":0}