{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778655773213,"sessionID":"ses_1dfdae888ffeP8VTJo6VqIXUjA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_6Gu6FL0pvc9gMtW4zEgYDhwC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/LESSONS.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/LESSONS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (broken, n/a): Source-use predicates may gate load-use stalls, but must not zero RVFI rs fields because cosim expects raw instruction rs bitfields and pre-read regfile values even for architecturally unused operands.\n2: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (improvement, +24.81%): Moving rare DIV/REM operations from the combinational ALU mux into an iterative EX side unit substantially improves Tang Nano 20K fitness because CoreMark pays little CPI cost while the common integer/MUL path loses a large divider critical path.\n3: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +9.57%): Static backward/JAL prediction in IF can lose more to fetch-path immediate decode and target-add critical path than it saves from CoreMark loop-branch flush avoidance.\n4: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -2.76%): Collapsing MULH/MULHU/MULHSU to one unsigned product plus high-half sign-correction subtractors can hurt Tang Nano 20K fitness because the added subtractor chain sits on the selected multiplier result path while parallel inferred multipliers are handled efficiently.\n5: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -17.61%): A two-entry IF skid buffer can cost more than it hides on CoreMark because queue_full/queue_empty/consume control and bypass timing outweigh limited fetch-ahead benefit under this single-issue front end.\n6: - 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -38.35%): Even a tiny IF-stage BTB can lose badly when tag compare/counter/target lookup becomes the fetch next-PC path, so CoreMark branch-penalty wins are not enough unless prediction metadata is off the Fmax-critical front end.\n7: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (regression, -3.35%): Source-aware load-use gating can regress when the added IF/ID opcode decode plus WB-stage RVFI source-value repair costs more Fmax/control complexity than CoreMark saves from eliminating false load bubbles.\n8: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -2.61%): Simply inserting an IF/ID register can regress because the new stall/flush/frontend_hold muxing and redirect-invalid handling outweigh breaking the imem_data-to-decode path unless retiming also simplifies front-end control.\n9: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (regression, -40.93%): Moving static prediction to ID still creates a same-cycle decode/immediate-add/stall-gated redirect into the IF PC mux, so the front-end critical path remains while EX also pays predicted-PC compare/correction logic.\n10: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r4s0 (improvement, +7.78%): Replacing MEM-stage variable shifts with explicit addr[1:0] byte-lane case muxes improves Tang Nano 20K fitness because CoreMark’s load/store-heavy path benefits from smaller dmem_rdata-to-WB and address-to-mask mux trees.\n11: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r4s1 (regression, -3.44%): Moving MULH/MULHU/MULHSU into an EX side unit can lose because low-half MUL still keeps the multiplier on the common path while high_mul stall/start/result muxing adds control cost that outweighs removing rare high-half product selection.\n12: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r4s2 (regression, -10.45%): Even a single-entry backward-loop predictor with a registered target can regress because the IF PC compare/target mux plus always-on EX predicted-next-PC correction cost more than CoreMark saves from repeat loop-back hits.\n13: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r5s0 (regression, -0.24%): Removing the regfile bulk reset did not improve Tang Nano 20K fitness, suggesting reset fanout/muxing on x1-x31 is not the binding path compared with the core's active decode, memory, and ALU datapaths.\n14: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r5s2 (regression, -48.07%): A return-only JALR target predictor is too narrow for CoreMark here; the IF PC compare/target mux plus carried predicted-PC EX correction cost overwhelms any saved return flushes.\n15: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r6s0 (regression, -4.12%): Pruning unused late-stage ctrl_t fields can regress because EX/MEM and MEM/WB control flops are not the binding path, while extra narrow-struct repacking and trap muxing add always-active control logic.\n16: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r6s1 (regression, +2.37%): MEM-stage load-data bypassing can regress when aligned dmem_rdata feeds directly into EX operand muxes, lengthening the memory-to-ALU path more than CoreMark benefits from removing one-cycle load-use bubbles.\n17: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r6s2 (improvement, +7.25%): A hot-branch predictor can pay off when the tag compare is shifted into a one-cycle sequential lookahead and the IF next-PC mux consumes only a registered prearmed target, preserving Fmax while recovering CoreMark loop-back bubbles.\n18: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r7s0 (regression, -22.32%): Deleting dead branch_taken/branch_target fields from EX/MEM can still hurt Tang Nano 20K fitness, reinforcing that late pipeline register width is not the binding path and small typedef changes may perturb packing/placement more than timing.\n19: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r7s1 (regression, -19.86%): Precomputing load/store masks, replicated wdata, aligned RVFI addr, and misalignment trap control in EX can hurt once MEM byte-lane muxing is simplified, because it shifts address-dependent gating onto the EX effective-address/control path rather than removing the true bottleneck.\n20: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r7s2 (regression, -22.20%): Expanding the registered lookahead predictor from one to two entries can lose because extra seq_pc tag compares, target priority muxing, and replacement state add IF arming complexity beyond CoreMark's remaining hot-edge thrash benefit.\n21: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r8s0 (regression, -53.91%): Forward direct JAL updates are not mere pollution for the one-entry registered lookahead predictor; filtering it to only backward targets can erase useful CoreMark call-site prediction and badly reduce fitness.\n22: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r8s1 (regression, -20.41%): Precomputing PC-relative adders in ID can regress when decode already sits on an active path; extra pc_plus4/pc_plus_imm adders and wider ID/EX flops may cost more than removing EX-side branch/JAL/AUIPC target adds.\n23: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r9s0 (regression, -16.56%): Special-casing MEM halfword masks/loads to addr[1] can regress despite architecturally unreachable misaligned lanes, suggesting the broader addr[1:0] case mux mapped better than the narrower aligned-only logic on this CoreMark path.\n24: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r9s1 (regression, -16.34%): Moving all MUL variants into an EX side unit regresses because CoreMark's low-half MUL frequency plus mul_wait/ex_busy stall control costs more than removing inferred multipliers from the common ALU mux.\n25: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r9s2 (regression, -6.38%): Requiring a second resolved hit before replacing the one-entry registered lookahead predictor can lose because delayed promotion sacrifices useful immediate CoreMark call/loop predictions while adding EX-update compare state without relieving the IF registered-target path.\n26: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r10s0 (regression, -11.10%): Replacing the EX predictor-update `branch_target < in.pc` comparator with `in.imm[31]` regressed, suggesting that compare was not the timing bottleneck and imm-bit/control remapping can perturb the hot predictor path more than it simplifies it.\n27: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r10s1 (regression, -10.06%): A single-entry store-drain buffer can cost more than it hides because store_buf_pending/dmem_ready arbitration lengthens MEM-stage dmem control and global stall logic while conservative CoreMark memory ordering leaves limited independent work under random store backpressure.\n28: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r10s2 (regression, -7.29%): Training the one-entry registered lookahead predictor on all taken conditional branches likely pollutes its hot loop/call target with forward biased branches, so the backward-branch direction filter is useful capacity management rather than just update-path complexity.\n29: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r11s0 (regression, -6.01%): Splitting signed compares into sign-bit muxing plus low-31 unsigned compares can regress because Tang Nano 20K appears to map generic `$signed <` efficiently while the extra branch/ALU select logic stays on hot EX paths.\n30: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r11s1 (regression, -13.39%): Factoring EX branch predicates into a compact shared branch_unit can regress because the subtractor/flag path and module factoring lose the efficient direct BEQ/BNE/signed/unsigned compare mapping on the hot redirect cone.\n31: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r11s2 (regression, -9.90%): Gating the EX predicted_pc_next correction compare with a carried predicted_taken bit did not relieve the hot redirect cone; the extra IF/ID/ID/EX state and redirect predicate control cost more than the skipped non-control compares.\n32: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r12s0 (regression, -14.09%): Suppressing EX/MEM load forwarding regressed because the load-use interlock already made that bypass case unreachable, while adding `ctrl.mem_read` into the forwarding priority logic put extra control on the hot EX operand mux path.\n33: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r12s1 (regression, -10.52%): Registering MEM/WB `wb_data` regressed because the writeback load-vs-ALU mux was not the limiting path, while adding a 32-bit late-stage field and moving selection into MEM increased register/placement cost without reducing CoreMark stalls.\n34: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r12s2 (regression, -16.30%): Redirect-target prearming regressed because adding a predictor-PC compare and armed-state update on the redirect path costs more timing/control than CoreMark gains from rare redirect-to-hot-control hits.\n35: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r13s0 (regression, -9.36%): Explicitly sharing EX-stage pc_plus4/pc_plus_imm adders can hurt because synthesis likely already commoned simple PC additions, while named shared wires increase fanout/routing across redirect, fallthrough, and jump-link cones.\n36: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r13s1 (regression, -9.82%): Even a one-entry current-PC fetch replay latch can regress because replay_valid/fetch_available muxing sits on IF output and global stall control while CoreMark gains little from overlapping imem responses with dmem/DIV stalls.\n37: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r13s2 (regression, -19.03%): Predecessor-keying the one-entry lookahead predictor regressed because the existing `seq_pc` adder fanout was not the binding IF cost, while `pred_update_pc - 4` retagging and changed compare placement perturbed the proven registered-target path.\n38: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r14s0 (regression, -27.11%): Manually sharing SLL/SRL/SRA through bit-reversal and staged barrel muxes can hurt EX timing because synthesis likely already maps native variable shifts well, while the explicit network adds op-dependent fill/reversal fanout on the hot ALU result path.\n39: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r14s2 (regression, -24.81%): Sticky loop protection for the one-entry lookahead predictor can backfire because loop_recent/admission control stays in IF update logic while blocking different forward JALs repeats the CoreMark call-site prediction loss seen with broader JAL filtering.\n\n(End of file - total 39 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (broken, n/a): Source-u