{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778655911180,"sessionID":"ses_1dfdae888ffeP8VTJo6VqIXUjA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_fLLrBHZDOfO9CCDXWa4Xp0DC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r15s1\n+title: \"Small instruction hit cache\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The tournament CoreMark mode injects roughly 22% random instruction-memory\n+  backpressure, and the current front end stalls the whole pipeline whenever\n+  io_imemReady is low. Prior fetch skid and replay latches only tried to\n+  overlap a single available response with backend stalls; they did not exploit\n+  CoreMark's repeated execution of a small hot code footprint. A tiny internal\n+  instruction cache can convert recurrent loop-body fetches into local hits and\n+  avoid many exposed iStall cycles without changing retirement width or the\n+  branch predictor policy.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a small direct-mapped instruction word cache inside the IF path with\n+  valid, tag, and 32-bit instruction arrays indexed by pc[6:2] or a similarly\n+  small power-of-two slice. On a cache hit, IF should present the cached\n+  instruction and assert an internal fetch-ready signal even when io_imemReady\n+  is low; on a miss, it should use the existing external imem response and fill\n+  the entry when io_imemReady is high, preserving fill-through so a ready miss\n+  has no extra latency. The hazard unit should stall on this internal\n+  fetch-ready signal rather than raw io_imemReady, while redirects and reset\n+  keep the cache contents coherent enough for the static benchmark image. This\n+  structural decoupling targets CoreMark iterations/cycle directly by removing\n+  repeated instruction-port stalls from hot loops, with the main risk being the\n+  added IF tag compare on Fmax.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a tiny direct-mapped instruction cache with hit/miss fill-through logic and an internal fetch-ready output used in place of raw io_imemReady.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire io_imemReady into IF, expose the IF cache hit/miss ready signal, and pass that signal to the hazard unit without changing the nret=1 RVFI port set.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Treat instruction fetch as stalled only when the IF-stage cache/memory fetch-ready signal is low, leaving load-use, dmem, redirect, and divide stall priorities unchanged.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,35 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r15s1\n+title: \"Small instruction hit cache\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The tournament CoreMark mode injects roughly 22% random instruction-memory\n+  backpressure, and the current front end stalls the whole pipeline whenever\n+  io_imemReady is low. Prior fetch skid and replay latches only tried to\n+  overlap a single available response with backend stalls; they did not exploit\n+  CoreMark's repeated execution of a small hot code footprint. A tiny internal\n+  instruction cache can convert recurrent loop-body fetches into local hits and\n+  avoid