{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778655917514,"sessionID":"ses_1dfdae888ffeP8VTJo6VqIXUjA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_hnW5f6skDDRNYsU5PUMuAZTq","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-002-r15s1\n2: title: \"Small instruction hit cache\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The tournament CoreMark mode injects roughly 22% random instruction-memory\n6:   backpressure, and the current front end stalls the whole pipeline whenever\n7:   io_imemReady is low. Prior fetch skid and replay latches only tried to\n8:   overlap a single available response with backend stalls; they did not exploit\n9:   CoreMark's repeated execution of a small hot code footprint. A tiny internal\n10:   instruction cache can convert recurrent loop-body fetches into local hits and\n11:   avoid many exposed iStall cycles without changing retirement width or the\n12:   branch predictor policy.\n13: hypothesis: |\n14:   Add a small direct-mapped instruction word cache inside the IF path with\n15:   valid, tag, and 32-bit instruction arrays indexed by pc[6:2] or a similarly\n16:   small power-of-two slice. On a cache hit, IF should present the cached\n17:   instruction and assert an internal fetch-ready signal even when io_imemReady\n18:   is low; on a miss, it should use the existing external imem response and fill\n19:   the entry when io_imemReady is high, preserving fill-through so a ready miss\n20:   has no extra latency. The hazard unit should stall on this internal\n21:   fetch-ready signal rather than raw io_imemReady, while redirects and reset\n22:   keep the cache contents coherent enough for the static benchmark image. This\n23:   structural decoupling targets CoreMark iterations/cycle directly by removing\n24:   repeated instruction-port stalls from hot loops, with the main risk being the\n25:   added IF tag compare on Fmax.\n26: expected_impact:\n27:   fitness_delta_pct: 6\n28:   confidence: medium\n29: changes:\n30:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n31:     description: \"Add a tiny direct-mapped instruction cache with hit/miss fill-through logic and an internal fetch-ready output used in place of raw io_imemReady.\"\n32:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n33:     description: \"Wire io_imemReady into IF, expose the IF cache hit/miss ready signal, and pass that signal to the hazard unit without changing the nret=1 RVFI port set.\"\n34:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n35:     description: \"Treat instruction fetch as stalled only when the IF-stage cache/memory fetch-ready signal is low, leaving load-use, dmem, redirect, and divide stall priorities unchanged.\"\n\n(End of file - total 35 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r15s1\ntitle: \"Small instruction hit cache\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The tournament CoreMark mode injects roughly 22% random instruction-memory\n  backpressure, and the current front end stalls the whole pipeline whenever\n  io_imemReady is low. Prior fetch skid and replay latches only tried to\n  overlap a single available response with backend stalls; they did not exploit\n  CoreMark's repeated execution of a small hot code footprint. A tiny internal\n  instruction cache can convert recurrent loop-body fetches into local hits and\n  avoid many exposed iStall cycles without changing retirement width or the\n  branch predictor policy.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add a small direct-mapped instruction word cache inside the IF path with\n  valid, tag, and 32-bit instruction arrays indexed by pc[6:2] or a similarly\n  small power-of-two slice. On a cache hit, IF should present the cached\n  instruction and assert an internal fetch-ready signal even when io_imemReady\n  is low; on a miss, it should use the existing external imem response and fill\n  the entry when io_imemReady is high, preserving fill-through so a ready miss\n  has no extra latency. The hazard unit should stall on this internal","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r15s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778655917508,"end":1778655917514}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e727b5c532ddb30016a0422ad2ebc81989be579ca0d8b63d9"}},"id":"prt_e20277529001YqEqHIfq83FWFq","sessionID":"ses_1dfdae888ffeP8VTJo6VqIXUjA","messageID":"msg_e20275d55001Mmr9TAa67OBsrS"}}
