{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778641986529,"sessionID":"ses_1e0adc4a6ffeJt5GhOClgitqS3","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_SrFjuhfaRsdbZg1YsdN2xQBH","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\n2: title: \"Source-aware load-use interlock\"\n3: category: micro_opt\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current load-use hazard compares the prior load destination against both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction. For many RV32I encodings one or both fields are not architecturally read, so the core can inject a one-cycle bubble after loads even when there is no true dependency. CoreMark has dense load, immediate, address-update, and control sequences, so eliminating false bubbles should improve iterations per cycle with very small RTL cost.\n6: hypothesis: |\n7:   Add compact IF/ID source-use predicates and gate the existing load-use comparison with them. Instructions that only read rs1, only read rs2, or read no integer source should not stall just because an immediate or destination bitfield happens to equal the load rd. The implementation must leave the raw instruction rs bitfields and regfile-read values unchanged through the pipeline so RVFI and cosim still see the same architectural source metadata; only the interlock predicate changes.\n8: expected_impact:\n9:   fitness_delta_pct: 3\n10:   confidence: medium\n11: changes:\n12:   - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n13:     description: \"Add IF/ID rs1_used and rs2_used inputs and apply them to the load-use dependency comparisons without changing other stall, flush, or hold priorities.\"\n14:   - file: rtl/core.sv\n15:     description: \"Derive compact source-use predicates from the IF/ID instruction opcode/funct class and pass them to the hazard unit while preserving all existing pipeline and RVFI source fields.\"\n\n(End of file - total 15 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\ntitle: \"Source-aware load-use interlock\"\ncategory: micro_opt\nmotivation: |\n  The current load-use hazard compares the prior load destination against both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction. For many RV32I encodings one or both fields are not architecturally read, so the core can inject a one-cycle bubble after loads even when there is no true dependency. CoreMark has dense load, immediate, address-update, and control sequences, so eliminating false bubbles should improve iterations per cycle with very small RTL cost.\nhypothesis: |\n  Add compact IF/ID source-use predicates and gate the existing load-use comparison with them. Instructions that only read rs1, only read rs2, or read no integer source should not stall just because an immediate or destination bitfield happens to equal the load rd. The implementation must leave the raw instruction rs bitfields and regfile-read values unchanged through the pipeline so RVFI and cosim still see the same architectural source metadata; only the interlock predicate changes.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n    description: \"Add IF/ID rs1_used and rs2_used inputs and apply them to the load-use dependency comparisons without changing other stall, flush, or hold priorities.\"\n  - file: rtl/core.sv\n    description: \"Derive compact source-use predicates from the IF/ID instruction opcode/funct class and pass them to the hazard unit while preserving all existing pipeline and RVFI source fields.\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-001-r3s0.yaml","time":{"start":1778641986522,"end":1778641986528}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0bafc0d274cccf7e016a03ec41e368819bbe55919416b214ca"}},"id":"prt_e1f52e1c6001NRdKYCEOs5Ao06","sessionID":"ses_1e0adc4a6ffeJt5GhOClgitqS3","messageID":"msg_e1f52d625001COhoxxKNZyaiXg"}}
