{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778641998487,"sessionID":"ses_1e0adc4a6ffeJt5GhOClgitqS3","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_88POFViky1AIjvnYcd8CF6MF","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\n+title: \"Register the IF/ID boundary\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end has no real IF/ID register: io_imemData feeds decode, immediate generation, regfile address selection, hazard inputs, and the ID/EX register in the same cycle. That structure keeps CPI low but likely puts external instruction-memory output, decoder fanout, and regfile read timing on one FPGA-critical path. Prior fetch-ahead structures lost badly because queue control and prediction logic made the front end more complex; a single registered IF/ID boundary is the minimal structural retiming that targets the same timing path without adding speculation or buffering policy.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Convert if_stage from a combinational IF/ID payload producer into a simple one-entry registered fetch/decode boundary. The PC still advances sequentially when the front end is not stalled, redirects still override stalls and flush the younger instruction, and ID consumes the registered instruction exactly as today. This should break the imem_data-to-decoder-to-ID/EX critical path and improve Fmax while preserving single-issue throughput; the expected CPI cost is limited to unchanged redirect/load-use behavior rather than the extra queue-control overhead seen in the failed skid-buffer attempt.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the combinational IF/ID output with a registered pc/instr/valid boundary, with redirect priority over stalls and explicit invalidation on flush or reset.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Adjust front-end stall/flush semantics for a registered IF/ID stage so load-use, imem backpressure, dmem stalls, EX busy, and redirects preserve existing priority without queue control.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the retimed IF/ID path through the existing top-level interfaces and keep the NRET=1 RVFI retirement contract unchanged.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\n+title: \"Register the IF/ID boundary\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end has no real IF/ID register: io_imemData feeds decode, immediate generation, regfile address selection, hazard inputs, and the ID/EX register in the same cycle. That structure keeps CPI low but likely puts external instruction-memory output, decoder fanout, and regfile read timing on one FPGA-critical path. Prior fetch-ahead structures lost badly because queue control and prediction logic made the front end more complex; a single registered IF/ID boundary is the minimal structural retiming that targets the same timing path without adding speculation or buffering policy.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Convert if_stage from a combinational IF/ID payload producer into a simple one-entry registered fetch/decode boundary. The PC still advances sequentially when the front end is not stalled, redirects still override stalls and flush the younger instruction, and ID consumes the registered instruction exactly as today. This should break the imem_data-to-decoder-to-ID/EX critical path and improve Fmax while preserving single-issue throughput; the expected CPI cost is limited to unchanged redirect/load-use behavior rather than the extra queue-control overhead seen in the failed skid-buffer attempt.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the combinational IF/ID output with a registered pc/instr/valid boundary, with redirect priority over stalls and explicit invalidation on flush or reset.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Adjust front-end stall/flush semantics for a registered IF/ID stage so load-use, imem backpressure, dmem stalls, EX busy, and redirects preserve existing priority without queue control.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the retimed IF/ID path through the existing top-level interfaces and keep the NRET=1 RVFI retirement contract unchanged.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r3s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\n+title: \"Register the IF/ID boundary\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current front end has no real IF/ID register: io_imemData feeds decode, immediate generation, regfile address selection, hazard inputs, and the ID/EX register in the same cycle. That structure keeps CPI low but likely puts external instruction-memory output, decoder fanout, and regfile read timing on one FPGA-critical path. Prior fetch-ahead structures lost badly because queue control and prediction logic made the front end more complex; a single registered IF/ID boundary is the minimal structural retiming that targets the same timing path without adding speculation or buffering policy.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Convert if_stage from a combinational IF/ID payload producer into a simple one-entry registered fetch/decode boundary. The PC still advances sequentially when the front end is not stalled, redirects still override stalls and flush the younger instruction, and ID consumes the registered instruction exactly as today. This should break the imem_data-to-decoder-to-ID/EX critical path and improve Fmax while preserving single-issue throughput; the expected CPI cost is limited to unchanged redirect/load-use behavior rather than the extra queue-control overhead seen in the failed skid-buffer attempt.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 5\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the combinational IF/ID output with a registered pc/instr/valid boundary, with redirect priority over stalls and explicit invalidation on flush or reset.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Adjust front-end stall/flush semantics for a registered IF/ID stage so load-use, imem backpressure, dmem stalls, EX busy, and redirects preserve existing priority without queue control.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the retimed IF/ID path through the existing top-level interfaces and keep the NRET=1 RVFI retirement contract unchanged.\"\n","addit