tag compare/counter/target lookup becomes the fetch next-PC path, so CoreMark branch-penalty wins are not enough unless prediction metadata is off the Fmax-critical front end.\n7: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (regression, -3.35%): Source-aware load-use gating can regress when the added IF/ID opcode decode plus WB-stage RVFI source-value repair costs more Fmax/control complexity than CoreMark saves from eliminating false load bubbles.\n8: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -2.61%): Simply inserting an IF/ID register can regress because the new stall/flush/frontend_hold muxing and redirect-invalid handling outweigh breaking the imem_data-to-decode path unless retiming also simplifies front-end control.\n9: - 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (regression, -40.93%): Moving static prediction to ID still creates a same-cycle decode/immediate-add/stall-gated redirect into the IF PC mux, so the front-end critical path remains while EX also pays predicted-PC compare/correction logic.\n\n(End of file - total 9 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r1s0 (broken, n/a): Source-use predicates may gate load-use stalls, but must not zero RVFI rs fields because cosim expects raw instruction rs bitfields and pre-read regfile values even for architecturally unused operands.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r1s1 (improvement, +24.81%): Moving rare DIV/REM operations from the combinational ALU mux into an iterative EX side unit substantially improves Tang Nano 20K fitness because CoreMark pays little CPI cost while the common integer/MUL path loses a large divider critical path.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r1s2 (regression, +9.57%): Static backward/JAL prediction in IF can lose more to fetch-path immediate decode and target-add critical path than it saves from CoreMark loop-branch flush avoidance.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-001-r2s0 (regression, -2.76%): Collapsing MULH/MULHU/MULHSU to one unsigned product plus high-half sign-correction subtractors can hurt Tang Nano 20K fitness because the added subtractor chain sits on the selected multiplier result path while parallel inferred multipliers are handled efficiently.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-002-r2s1 (regression, -17.61%): A two-entry IF skid buffer can cost more than it hides on CoreMark because queue_full/queue_empty/consume control and bypass timing outweigh limited fetch-ahead benefit under this single-issue front end.\n- 2026-05-12 hyp-20260512-003-r2s2 (regression, -38.35%): Even a tiny IF-stage BTB can lose badly when tag compare/counter/target lookup becomes the fetch next-PC path, so CoreMark branch-penalty wins are not enough unless prediction metadata is off the Fmax-critical front end.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-001-r3s0 (regression, -3.35%): Source-aware load-use gating can regress when the added IF/ID opcode decode plus WB-stage RVFI source-value repair costs more Fmax/control complexity than CoreMark saves from eliminating false load bubbles.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-002-r3s1 (regression, -2.61%): Simply inserting an IF/ID register can regress because the new stall/flush/frontend_hold muxing and redirect-invalid handling outweigh breaking the imem_data-to-decode path unless retiming also simplifies front-end control.\n- 2026-05-13 hyp-20260513-003-r3s2 (regression, -40.93%): Moving static prediction to ID still creates a same-cycle decode/immediate-add/stall-gated redirect into the IF PC mux, so the front-end critical path remains while EX also pays predicted-PC compare/correction logic.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/LESSONS.md","time":{"start":1778642885753,"end":1778642885760}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_03b77f508373af4b016a03efc5a57c819a849158812651690c"}},"id":"prt_e1f609c69001sGOhQ4WiMrdfyc","sessionID":"ses_1e09f8876ffe9aqIZzQ4X2m5ie","messageID":"msg_e1f6077cb001l7BkVrOrY8i4HH"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778642885765,"sessionID":"ses_1e09f8876ffe9aqIZzQ4X2m5ie","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_LPnaFBtOq0X9XAjtiOXikM27","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"category: structural|structural|pipeline|stage|bypass|forward|retime|register|skid|buffer|predict","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 7 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Move DIV/REM off the ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current execute stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU, including\\nSystemVerilog division and remainder operators in the same result mux as the\\ncommon RV32I and MUL operations. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely bloats LUT\\nusage and lengthens the EX critical path even though CoreMark is dominated by\\nordinary integer, load/store, branch, and multiply instructions rather than\\ndivide/remainder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current execute stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU, including\\nSystemVerilog division and remainder operators in the same result mux as the\\ncommon RV32I and MUL operations. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely bloats LUT\\nusage and lengthens the EX critical path even though CoreMark is dominated by\\nordinary integer, load/store, branch, and multiply instructions rather than\\ndivide/remainder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a small iterative\\nmulti-cycle M-extension side unit in EX. Keep ADD/SUB/logic/shift/compare and\\nthe MUL-family operations on the existing single-cycle path, but detect divide\\nand remainder opcodes in EX, start the divider, and stall the pipeline until\\nthe result is available. This structural decoupling should reduce the normal\\nALU critical path and LUT pressure with negligible CoreMark CPI cost because\\nrare DIV/REM instructions pay the added latency only when they occur.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real DIV/REM operators from the combinational ALU path while preserving ALTOPS behavior for formal builds.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add DIV/REM detection, launch/consume the iterative result, and hold the EX/MEM register while a divide operation is in progress.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\":...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken loop branch or JAL pays a two-instruction flush penalty. CoreMark has tight loops and frequent backward branches, making a very small front-end predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without the LUT and Fmax cost of a larger dynamic predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken loop branch or JAL pays a two-instruction flush penalty. CoreMark has tight loops and frequent backward branches, making a very small front-end predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without the LUT and Fmax cost of a larger dynamic predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a static predict-taken path in IF for aligned backward conditional branches and aligned unconditional JAL, while keeping forward conditional branches predicted not-taken and JALR resolved in EX. Carry the predicted next PC through ID/EX, compare it against the actual EX-resolved next PC, and redirect only on mispredict. This should remove most loop-back branch penalties with only immediate decode/add logic in the fetch path and no predictor RAM state.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles so EX can validate the IF-stage prediction while preserving RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode fetched branch/JAL immediates in IF and choose aligned pc+imm for backward conditional branches and JAL, otherwise pc+4; emit the chosen predicted next PC with the fetched instruction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Latch the IF-stage predicted next PC into ID/EX alongside the existing decoded instruction metadata.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage....\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Decoupled fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end is tightly coupled to the rest of the pipeline: any\\ndmem stall, load-use stall, divide stall, or raw imem-not-ready cycle holds\\nthe PC and prevents useful fetch progress. In the tournament CoreMark mode\\nboth instruction and data ports see random backpressure, so exposed fetch\\nbubbles reduce iterations per cycle even when the instruction port could\\nhave fetched ahead during unrelated back-end stalls.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end is tightly coupled to the rest of the pipeline: any\\ndmem stall, load-use stall, divide stall, or raw imem-not-ready cycle holds\\nthe PC and prevents useful fetch progress. In the tournament CoreMark mode\\nboth instruction and data ports see random backpressure, so exposed fetch\\nbubbles reduce iterations per cycle even when the instruction port could\\nhave fetched ahead during unrelated back-end stalls.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny two-entry fetch skid buffer between IF and ID. The IF stage should\\nkeep issuing sequential fetches while the decode/back-end side is stalled and\\nthere is queue space, and ID should consume from the queue whenever it can\\nadvance. Redirects still flush the queue and restart at the resolved target,\\npreserving the current EX-resolution semantics and RVFI ordering. This\\nstructural decoupling should hide a fraction of random imem stalls behind\\ndmem/load-use/div stalls with modest LUT/FF cost and less timing risk than\\nputting branch prediction logic back on the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the purely combinational IF/ID payload with a small valid-ready fetch queue that can fill while ID is stalled, drains to ID when available, and flushes on redirect.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Base front-end stalls ...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny BTB branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so tight CoreMark\\nloops pay a two-instruction redirect penalty on each taken iteration. The prior\\nstatic backward predictor showed that avoiding these penalties can help CPI,\\nbut its IF-stage immediate decode and target add hurt Fmax enough to lose most\\nof the gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so tight CoreMark\\nloops pay a two-instruction redirect penalty on each taken iteration. The prior\\nstatic backward predictor showed that avoiding these penalties can help CPI,\\nbut its IF-stage immediate decode and target add hurt Fmax enough to lose most\\nof the gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small direct-mapped BTB with 2-bit saturating counters, updated only from\\nresolved control-flow instructions in EX. IF predicts taken only on a valid tag\\nhit with a taken counter and uses the stored target, otherwise it fetches pc+4;\\nthis keeps branch immediate decode and target addition out of the fetch path.\\nCarry predicted next-PC metadata through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX redirects only\\nwhen the stored prediction disagrees with the actual resolved next PC. This\\nshould recover most repeated loop-branch and unconditional jump penalties after\\nwarm-up with lower Fmax risk than the failed static predictor.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted next-PC and prediction-valid metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Implement a small direct-mapped BTB/BHT lookup in IF, select stored targets on confident tag hits, and update entries from EX resolution signals.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Latch IF prediction metadata into ID/EX without changing raw instruction rs fields or RVFI-visible...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Source-aware load-use interlock\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard compares the prior load destination against both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction. For many RV32I encodings one or both fields are not architecturally read, so the core can inject a one-cycle bubble after loads even when there is no true dependency. CoreMark has dense load, immediate, address-update, and control sequences, so eliminating false bubbles should improve iterations per cycle with very small RTL cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard compares the prior load destination against both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction. For many RV32I encodings one or both fields are not architecturally read, so the core can inject a one-cycle bubble after loads even when there is no true dependency. CoreMark has dense load, immediate, address-update, and control sequences, so eliminating false bubbles should improve iterations per cycle with very small RTL cost.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add compact IF/ID source-use predicates and gate the existing load-use comparison with them. Instructions that only read rs1, only read rs2, or read no integer source should not stall just because an immediate or destination bitfield happens to equal the load rd. The implementation must leave the raw instruction rs bitfields and regfile-read values unchanged through the pipeline so RVFI and cosim still see the same architectural source metadata; only the interlock predicate changes.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Add IF/ID rs1_used and rs2_used inputs and apply them to the load-use dependency comparisons without changing other stall, flush, or hold priorities.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Derive compact source-use predicates from the IF/ID instruction opcode/funct class and...\n  Line 9: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r3s1\", \"title\": \"Register the IF/ID boundary\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID register: io_imemData feeds decode, immediate generation, regfile address selection, hazard inputs, and the ID/EX register in the same cycle. That structure keeps CPI low but likely puts external instruction-memory output, decoder fanout, and regfile read timing on one FPGA-critical path. Prior fetch-ahead structures lost badly because queue control and prediction logic made the front end more complex; a single registered IF/ID boundary is the minimal structural retiming that targets the same timing path without adding speculation or buffering policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID register: io_imemData feeds decode, immediate generation, regfile address selection, hazard inputs, and the ID/EX register in the same cycle. That structure keeps CPI low but likely puts external instruction-memory output, decoder fanout, and regfile read timing on one FPGA-critical path. Prior fetch-ahead structures lost badly because queue control and prediction logic made the front end more complex; a single registered IF/ID boundary is the minimal structural retiming that targets the same timing path without adding speculation or buffering policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert if_stage from a combinational IF/ID payload producer into a simple one-entry registered fetch/decode boundary. The PC still advances sequentially when the front end is not stalled, redirects still override stalls and flush the younger instruction, and ID consumes the registered instruction exactly as today. This should break the imem_data-to-decoder-to-ID/EX critical path and improve Fmax while preserving single-issue throughput; the expected CPI cost is limited to unchanged redirect/load-use behavior rather than the extra queue-control overhead seen in the failed skid-buffer attempt.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"ID-stage static control predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so CoreMark loop\\nbacks and direct jumps pay a two-instruction wrong-path flush. Prior IF-stage\\nstatic and BTB predictors showed that eliminating this penalty can help CPI,\\nbut putting immediate decode, target add, tag compare, or predictor RAM lookup\\non the fetch next-PC path costs too much Fmax on Tang Nano 20K.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so CoreMark loop\\nbacks and direct jumps pay a two-instruction wrong-path flush. Prior IF-stage\\nstatic and BTB predictors showed that eliminating this penalty can help CPI,\\nbut putting immediate decode, target add, tag compare, or predictor RAM lookup\\non the fetch next-PC path costs too much Fmax on Tang Nano 20K.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the lightweight static predictor out of IF and into ID. IF should remain\\na simple sequential pc+4 fetch unless an existing redirect arrives, while ID\\ndecodes the fetched instruction and redirects one stage early for aligned JAL\\nand aligned backward conditional branches. Carry the ID-predicted next PC into\\nEX so the branch/jump resolver redirects only when the actual next PC differs\\nfrom the prediction. This keeps predictor work off the front-end critical path\\nand still saves one of the two taken-control-flow bubbles in CoreMark loops.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an ID/EX predicted-next-PC field so EX can compare the static ID prediction with the actual resolved next PC.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ID-stage prediction redirect signals to IF and route the carried predicted next PC into EX resolution.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept an ID-stage prediction redirect with lower priority than EX correctio...","metadata":{"matches":7,"truncated":false},"title":"category: structural|structural|pipeline|stage|bypass|forward|retime|register|skid|buffer|predict","time":{"start":1778642885756,"end":1778642885765}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_03b77f508373af4b016a03efc5a58c819aa1b4734958c77931"}},"id":"prt_e1f609c7b0019uHKoZju91wZkO","sessionID":"ses_1e09f8876ffe9aqIZzQ4X2m5ie","messageID":"msg_e1f6077cb001l7BkVrOrY8i4HH"}}
