{"type":"text","timestamp":1778644992550,"sessionID":"ses_1e07ff939ffeAp8h4DXzwHtrbi","part":{"id":"prt_e1f80c188001S84qycRRGz3sNT","messageID":"msg_e1f802dcd001iFBvmUYOd3OTr3","sessionID":"ses_1e07ff939ffeAp8h4DXzwHtrbi","type":"text","text":"The prior structural wins are concentrated in removing uncommon long paths, while front-end queues/registering and prediction have regressed. The most promising remaining structural angle is a selective store buffer that hides random data-port stalls after stores without adding fetch critical-path logic.","time":{"start":1778644992392,"end":1778644992549},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0ba4d880487aedf4016a03f80048f0819b96a44fb0c9297fcb","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778644998893,"sessionID":"ses_1e07ff939ffeAp8h4DXzwHtrbi","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_NNSvH2jIXcCCE46Eywc4UZ0z","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Selective store stall bypass\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline freezes globally whenever a STORE reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. In the tournament CoreMark mode the data port has random backpressure, so store stalls unnecessarily block later independent ALU, branch, and multiply work even though the store payload is already fully known at MEM. Prior front-end decoupling attempts regressed because they added timing-critical fetch control; a back-end-only decoupling point should target IPC under dStall with less fetch-path risk.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry store buffer at the MEM boundary for aligned, non-MMIO stores. When a normal store reaches MEM and dmem is not ready, capture its address, replicated write data, and byte mask, allow the store to retire through MEM/WB, and keep driving the buffered write until the bus accepts it. While the buffer is occupied, stall only younger LOAD/STORE instructions to preserve memory ordering and the single dmem port; let younger non-memory instructions continue. Do not buffer UART or timing-marker MMIO stores so CoreMark brackets and output ordering remain exact. This should hide a fraction of random store backpressure cycles without changing nret, branch behavior, or common EX timing.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry non-MMIO store buffer, drive buffered writes on the dmem port until accepted, and retire buffered stores through MEM/WB without double-retirement.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the current all-memory dmem stall policy with store-buffer-aware stalls that block loads/stores when ordering or buffer capacity requires it but allow younger non-memory operations to proceed.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire store-buffer status and separate EX/MEM load/store control into the hazard unit while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Selective store stall bypass\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline freezes globally whenever a STORE reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. In the tournament CoreMark mode the data port has random backpressure, so store stalls unnecessarily block later independent ALU, branch, and multiply work even though the store payload is already fully known at MEM. Prior front-end decoupling attempts regressed because they added timing-critical fetch control; a back-end-only decoupling point should target IPC under dStall with less fetch-path risk.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry store buffer at the MEM boundary for aligned, non-MMIO stores. When a normal store reaches MEM and dmem is not ready, capture its address, replicated write data, and byte mask, allow the store to retire through MEM/WB, and keep driving the buffered write until the bus accepts it. While the buffer is occupied, stall only younger LOAD/STORE instructions to preserve memory ordering and the single dmem port; let younger non-memory instructions continue. Do not buffer UART or timing-marker MMIO stores so CoreMark brackets and output ordering remain exact. This should hide a fraction of random store backpressure cycles without changing nret, branch behavior, or common EX timing.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry non-MMIO store buffer, drive buffered writes on the dmem port until accepted, and retire buffered stores through MEM/WB without double-retirement.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the current all-memory dmem stall policy with store-buffer-aware stalls that block loads/stores when ordering or buffer capacity requires it but allow younger non-memory operations to proceed.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire store-buffer status and separate EX/MEM load/store control into the hazard unit while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port contract.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,17 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\n+title: \"Selective store stall bypass\"\n+category: structural\n+motivation: |\n+  The current pipeline freezes globally whenever a STORE reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. In the tournament CoreMark mode the data port has random backpressure, so store stalls unnecessarily block later independent ALU, branch, and multiply work even though the store payload is already fully known at MEM. Prior front-end decoupling attempts regressed because they added timing-critical fetch control; a back-end-only decoupling point should target IPC under dStall with less fetch-path risk.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a one-entry store buffer at the MEM boundary for aligned, non-MMIO stores. When a normal store reaches MEM and dmem is not ready, capture its address, replicated write data, and byte mask, allow the store to retire through MEM/WB, and keep driving the buffered write until the bus accepts it. While the buffer is occupied, stall only younger LOAD/STORE instructions to preserve memory ordering and the single dmem port; let younger non-memory instructions continue. Do not buffer UART or timing-marker MMIO stores so CoreMark brackets and output ordering remain exact. This should hide a fraction of random store backpressure cycles without changing nret, branch behavior, or common EX timing.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 6\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry non-MMIO store buffer, drive buffered writes on the dmem port until accepted, and retire buffered stores through MEM/WB without double-retirement.\"\n+  - file: rtl/hazard_unit.sv\n+    description: \"Replace the current all-memory dmem stall policy with store-buffer-aware stalls that block loads/stores when ordering or buffer capacity requires it but allow younger non-memory operations to proceed.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire store-buffer status and separate EX/MEM load/store control into the hazard unit while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port contract.\"\n","additions":17,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r5s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778644998886,"end":1778644998892}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0ba4d880487aedf4016a03f80068d0819b90aa544b24e9e77a"}},"id":"prt_e1f80c226001cTQMbQZzPgrnDs","sessionID":"ses_1e07ff939ffeAp8h4DXzwHtrbi","messageID":"msg_e1f802dcd001iFBvmUYOd3OTr3"}}
