{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778646631834,"sessionID":"ses_1e0674ce5ffea7me2DnuLapAU9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_MnzgRnIpbg80S29qSiEsNUkU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","offset":1,"limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\n2: title: \"Precompute MEM access descriptor in EX\"\n3: category: structural\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The strongest recent non-predictor gain came from simplifying MEM-stage byte-lane muxing, which suggests the load/store formatting path is still important for Tang Nano 20K fitness. The current MEM stage still derives misalignment, byte masks, replicated store data, aligned RVFI addresses, and dmem enables in the same cycle that dmem_rdata is selected and forwarded to writeback. Front-end queues, IF retiming, high-multiply side units, and direct load-data bypassing have already shown poor tradeoffs, so the next structural target should be a no-CPI retiming of an existing hot back-end path.\n6: hypothesis: |\n7:   Move the address-dependent memory access descriptor generation from MEM into EX, immediately after the effective address is computed. EX should precompute the byte mask, replicated store data, word-aligned RVFI address, memory-misalignment trap bit, and trap-gated control for load/store instructions, then carry those registered fields in EX/MEM. MEM can then drive dmem_wen/dmem_ren, RVFI masks, and store write data mostly from registered descriptor fields while retaining the existing load-data extraction from dmem_rdata. This should shorten the MEM address/control-to-writeback and dmem-enable paths with no CPI cost, while adding only small EX-side logic based on alu_result[1:0] and existing memory control bits.\n8: expected_impact:\n9:   fitness_delta_pct: 3\n10:   confidence: medium\n11: changes:\n12:   - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n13:     description: \"Extend ex_mem_t with registered memory descriptor fields such as replicated store data, byte mask, aligned RVFI address, and a precomputed misalignment/trap indication.\"\n14:   - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n15:     description: \"After computing the effective address, generate the load/store byte mask, replicated store data, aligned address, and memory-misalignment trap state, and latch those fields into EX/MEM while preserving existing branch, DIV, and RVFI behavior.\"\n16:   - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n17:     description: \"Replace MEM-stage address-dependent mask, store-data, aligned-address, and misalignment generation with use of the registered EX/MEM descriptor, leaving load-data byte/halfword extraction and RVFI memory reporting intact.\"\n\n(End of file - total 17 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\ntitle: \"Precompute MEM access descriptor in EX\"\ncategory: structural\nmotivation: |\n  The strongest recent non-predictor gain came from simplifying MEM-stage byte-lane muxing, which suggests the load/store formatting path is still important for Tang Nano 20K fitness. The current MEM stage still derives misalignment, byte masks, replicated store data, aligned RVFI addresses, and dmem enables in the same cycle that dmem_rdata is selected and forwarded to writeback. Front-end queues, IF retiming, high-multiply side units, and direct load-data bypassing have already shown poor tradeoffs, so the next structural target should be a no-CPI retiming of an existing hot back-end path.\nhypothesis: |\n  Move the address-dependent memory access descriptor generation from MEM into EX, immediately after the effective address is computed. EX should precompute the byte mask, replicated store data, word-aligned RVFI address, memory-misalignment trap bit, and trap-gated control for load/store instructions, then carry those registered fields in EX/MEM. MEM can then drive dmem_wen/dmem_ren, RVFI masks, and store write data mostly from registered descriptor fields while retaining the existing load-data extraction from dmem_rdata. This should shorten the MEM address/control-to-writeback and dmem-enable paths with no CPI cost, while adding only small EX-side logic based on alu_result[1:0] and existing memory control bits.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n    description: \"Extend ex_mem_t with registered memory descriptor fields such as replicated store data, byte mask, aligned RVFI address, and a precomputed misalignment/trap indication.\"\n  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n    description: \"After computing the effective address, generate the load/store byte mask, replicated store data, aligned address, and memory-misalignment trap state, and latch those fields into EX/MEM while preserving existing branch, DIV, and RVFI behavior.\"\n  - file: rtl/mem_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace MEM-stage address-dependent mask, store-data, aligned-address, and misalignment generation with use of the registered EX/MEM descriptor, leaving load-data byte/halfword extraction and RVFI memory reporting intact.\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-002-r7s1.yaml","time":{"start":1778646631830,"end":1778646631834}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c888337cbb8678d016a03fe6784ec819a898eb5d5653f6b0a"}},"id":"prt_e1f99c4bc001d6vzX27FR3ow0d","sessionID":"ses_1e0674ce5ffea7me2DnuLapAU9","messageID":"msg_e1f99b1b0002xakOR2p2EZN2SA"}}
