{"type":"text","timestamp":1778648678037,"sessionID":"ses_1e047495bffeJfUrSCjYHqe3vM","part":{"id":"prt_e1fb8fe15002U9briddrO6QcmE","messageID":"msg_e1fb8da7e001Ze3O6aLeq7rxt0","sessionID":"ses_1e047495bffeJfUrSCjYHqe3vM","type":"text","text":"The history confirms several structural directions are already negative: front-end buffering/retiming, high-half multiply side units, MEM descriptor retiming, and load-result bypass all lost. I’m checking the one structural store-buffer attempt before choosing a non-overlapping proposal.","time":{"start":1778648677909,"end":1778648678036},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_096f269998205fed016a040665d1248199af8c64b991eb3463","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778648678793,"sessionID":"ses_1e047495bffeJfUrSCjYHqe3vM","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_sb2MXXiZUhEZ6n5Y9ZKTRw3x","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":15,"limit":1},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n15: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Selective store stall bypass\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes globally whenever a STORE reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. In the tournament CoreMark mode the data port has random backpressure, so store stalls unnecessarily block later independent ALU, branch, and multiply work even though the store payload is already fully known at MEM. Prior front-end decoupling attempts regressed because they added timing-critical fetch control; a back-end-only decoupling point should target IPC under dStall with less fetch-path risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes globally whenever a STORE reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. In the tournament CoreMark mode the data port has random backpressure, so store stalls unnecessarily block later independent ALU, branch, and multiply work even though the store payload is already fully known at MEM. Prior front-end decoupling attempts regressed because they added timing-critical fetch control; a back-end-only decoupling point should target IPC under dStall with less fetch-path risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry store buffer at the MEM boundary for aligned, non-MMIO stores. When a normal store reaches MEM and dmem is not ready, capture its address, replicated write data, and byte mask, allow the store to retire through MEM/WB, and keep driving the buffered write until the bus accepts it. While the buffer is occupied, stall only younger LOAD/STORE instructions to preserve memory ordering and the single dmem port; let younger non-memory instructions continue. Do not buffer UART or timing-marker MMIO stores so CoreMark brackets and output ordering remain exact. This should hide a fraction of random store backpressure cycles without changing nret, branch behavior, or common EX timing.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a one... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(Showing lines 15-15 of 25. Use offset=16 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r5s1\", \"title\": \"Selective store stall bypass\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes globally whenever a STORE reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. In the tournament CoreMark mode the data port has random backpressure, so store stalls unnecessarily block later independent ALU, branch, and multiply work even though the store payload is already fully known at MEM. Prior front-end decoupling attempts regressed because they added timing-critical fetch control; a back-end-only decoupling point should target IPC under dStall with less fetch-path risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current pipeline freezes globally whenever a STORE reaches MEM while io_dmemReady is low. In the tournament CoreMark mode the data port has random backpressure, so store stalls unnecessarily block later independent ALU, branch, and multiply work even though the store payload is already fully known at MEM. Prior front-end decoupling attempts regressed because they added timing-critical fetch control; a back-end-only decoupling point should target IPC under dStall with less fetch-path risk.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry store buffer at the MEM boundary for aligned, non-MMIO stores. When a normal store reaches MEM and dmem is not ready, capture its address, replicated write data, and byte mask, allow the store to retire through MEM/WB, and keep driving the buffered write until the bus accepts it. While the buffer is occupied, stall only younger LOAD/STORE instructions to preserve memory ordering and the single dmem port; let younger non-memory instructions continue. Do not buffer UART or timing-marker MMIO stores so CoreMark brackets and output ordering remain exact. This should hide a fraction of random store backpressure cycles without changing nret, branch behavior, or common EX timing.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add a one... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778648678790,"end":1778648678793}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_096f269998205fed016a040665f02881999ef9d73941886a95"}},"id":"prt_e1fb8fe95001KS2kbrn6TIvz0n","sessionID":"ses_1e047495bffeJfUrSCjYHqe3vM","messageID":"msg_e1fb8da7e001Ze3O6aLeq7rxt0"}}
