{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778650311970,"sessionID":"ses_1e0306013ffea8EiV328ilAJxS","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_bTLyqcVOXBn7IdCRIcdf2S9M","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r10s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r10s2\n+title: Directionless hot-edge training\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The current one-entry registered lookahead predictor is the only predictor variant\n+  that improved fitness because it keeps tag comparison off the current IF next-PC\n+  mux. Later predictor regressions came from adding IF lookup complexity or delaying\n+  useful updates. A narrower update-policy change can try to recover more CoreMark\n+  control-flow bubbles while preserving the successful IF timing shape.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Train the existing one-entry lookahead predictor on every resolved taken\n+  conditional branch, not only taken backward branches, while continuing to train on\n+  direct JALs and still excluding JALR. This removes the branch_target < pc direction\n+  filter from the EX update path and lets the same registered prearmed target\n+  mechanism learn hot forward taken branches in CoreMark. Correctness is unchanged\n+  because EX already carries predicted_pc_next and redirects on any mismatch, so\n+  biased branches that later fall through are repaired exactly like loop exits.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: medium\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Broaden pred_update_valid so the existing one-entry lookahead predictor trains on all legal taken conditional branches plus direct JALs, removing the backward-target direction check without adding IF-stage lookup logic.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r10s2.