{"type":"text","timestamp":1778654498097,"sessionID":"ses_1dfee91c7ffeyWt73JHJ32TtO9","part":{"id":"prt_e2011c95d001d7V6Nf1HXmXnO2","messageID":"msg_e201193d3001bwJ1QqWwfWM2R1","sessionID":"ses_1dfee91c7ffeyWt73JHJ32TtO9","type":"text","text":"The history points strongly toward preserving the one-entry registered lookahead predictor shape: it was the only predictor win, while extra IF compares, redirect prearming, delayed promotion, and broad update-policy changes all regressed. I’ll write a focused hypothesis that keeps the fetch datapath unchanged and only changes EX update admission to reduce one-entry thrash without adding lookup state.","time":{"start":1778654497117,"end":1778654498096},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_00e5fb42643675f1016a041d21076c8198b1f295ce0a172527","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778654527023,"sessionID":"ses_1dfee91c7ffeyWt73JHJ32TtO9","part":{"id":"prt_e20123d54001iNzEAr7uUZcrEn","messageID":"msg_e201193d3001bwJ1QqWwfWM2R1","sessionID":"ses_1dfee91c7ffeyWt73JHJ32TtO9","type":"text","text":"I’m going to add the hypothesis file now. The proposal is intentionally narrow: add a “recently used loop entry” guard to the existing one-entry lookahead predictor update path, without adding another IF lookup entry or changing the registered armed-target mux.","time":{"start":1778654526804,"end":1778654527021},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_00e5fb42643675f1016a041d3eb58c8198bdb6f09a48224e33","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778654530527,"sessionID":"ses_1dfee91c7ffeyWt73JHJ32TtO9","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_FwzfaQpYWxQNcXeBWVmw7r3y","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r14s2\n+title: Sticky loop lookahead predictor\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The only predictor variant that improved this core is the current one-entry\n+  registered lookahead predictor, because IF consumes only prearmed registered\n+  state. Follow-up attempts regressed when they added IF lookup entries,\n+  redirect-path prearming, candidate promotion, carried validation bits, or\n+  broad update-policy changes. The remaining promising predictor angle is to\n+  preserve the proven fetch datapath while making the single entry less likely\n+  to be overwritten by lower-value direct jumps immediately after it proves\n+  useful for a hot loop branch.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a small update-admission guard to the existing one-entry lookahead\n+  predictor: remember when the active entry was a backward conditional branch\n+  and was just consumed as an armed prediction, and for a short window refuse\n+  to replace that active loop entry with a different forward direct JAL. Taken\n+  backward branches still update immediately, direct JALs still refresh their\n+  own entry and can fill an empty/non-loop entry, and the IF-side lookup remains\n+  exactly one registered prearm compare feeding one registered target mux. This\n+  should reduce one-entry thrash between hot CoreMark loop backs and nearby\n+  calls without repeating the failed all-JAL filtering or two-entry IF lookup\n+  experiments.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Track whether the active predictor entry is a backward-branch loop entry, mark it recently used when its armed prediction is consumed, and gate replacement by different direct-JAL updates while keeping the IF lookup and next-PC mux one-entry/registered.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose whether each predictor update came from a taken backward conditional branch or a direct JAL so if_stage can apply loop-entry replacement priority without changing redirect, RVFI pc_next, or trap behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the predictor update class signal from EX to IF alongside the existing update valid, PC, and target signals.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,33 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r14s2\n+title: Sticky loop lookahead predictor\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The only predictor variant that improved this core is the current one-entry\n+  registered lookahead predictor, because IF consumes only prearmed registered\n+  state. Follow-up attempts regressed when they added IF lookup entries,\n+  redirect-path prearming, candidate promotion, carried validation bits, or\n+  broad update-policy changes. The remaining promising predictor angle is to\n+  preserve the proven fetch datapath while making the single entry less likely\n+  to be overwritten by lower-value direct jumps immediately after it proves\n+  useful for a hot loop branch.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a small update-admission guard to the existing one-entry lookahead\n+  predictor: remember when the active entry was a backward conditional branch\n+  and was just consumed as an armed prediction, and for a short window refuse\n+  to replace that active loop entry with a different forward direct JAL. Taken\n+  backward branches still update immediately, direct JALs still refresh their\n+  own entry and can fill an empty/non-loop entry, and the IF-side lookup remains\n+  exactly one registered prearm compare feeding one registered target mux. This\n+  should reduce one-entry thrash between hot CoreMark loop backs and nearby\n+  calls without repeating the failed all-JAL filtering or two-entry IF lookup\n+  experiments.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Track whether the active predictor entry is a backward-branch loop entry, mark it recently used when its armed prediction is consumed, and gate replacement by different direct-JAL updates while keeping the IF lookup and next-PC mux one-entry/registered.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose whether each predictor update came from a taken backward conditional branch or a direct JAL so if_stage can apply loop-entry replacement priority without changing redirect, RVFI pc_next, or trap behavior.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire the predictor update class signal from EX to IF alongside the existing update valid, PC, and target signals.\"\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml","relativePath":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r14s2.yaml\n==================================================================