{"type":"text","timestamp":1778642904217,"sessionID":"ses_1e09f87a1ffe9DUP2PLMjWxOcd","part":{"id":"prt_e1f60e347001jY71rNn1x3dx5o","messageID":"msg_e1f60ab52002ihGllsi4YRy0XD","sessionID":"ses_1e09f87a1ffe9DUP2PLMjWxOcd","type":"text","text":"Prior predictor attempts all lost when they inserted decode, target-add, BTB tag lookup, or same-cycle ID redirect into the PC path. The least risky predictor hypothesis is therefore a very narrow single-entry loop predictor that only handles the last resolved taken backward branch and uses a registered target, avoiding immediate decode and RAM lookup.","time":{"start":1778642903879,"end":1778642904217},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_00e6083a15b101ac016a03efd7c938819890ef21e307b91480","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1778642916391,"sessionID":"ses_1e09f87a1ffe9DUP2PLMjWxOcd","part":{"id":"prt_e1f61138e0012ZkLwVfO1UpxuO","messageID":"msg_e1f60ab52002ihGllsi4YRy0XD","sessionID":"ses_1e09f87a1ffe9DUP2PLMjWxOcd","type":"text","text":"I’m writing a narrow predictor hypothesis: one-entry backward-loop target replay updated at EX resolution, with predicted-next-PC metadata so EX can correct only on mismatch.","time":{"start":1778642916238,"end":1778642916390},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_00e6083a15b101ac016a03efe422448198823cb9f61e516d53","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778642922725,"sessionID":"ses_1e09f87a1ffe9DUP2PLMjWxOcd","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_kEtFRssVxnlsmza6FtGvpc6N","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\n+title: \"Single-entry loop target predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The failed predictor attempts show that broad prediction logic loses when it adds immediate decode, target adders, RAM lookup, counters, or same-cycle ID redirect control to the front-end critical path. CoreMark still has repeated loop-back branches that pay the current EX-resolution flush penalty, so the best remaining predictor angle is a much narrower mechanism that only learns the last hot backward branch target and keeps all target computation in EX.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry last-taken backward-branch predictor updated from resolved EX-stage branches. IF predicts taken only when the current PC exactly matches the stored branch PC, using the already-registered target from the entry; all other fetches stay simple pc+4, and no instruction immediate decode or branch target addition occurs in IF. Carry the predicted next PC through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX redirects only when the actual resolved next PC differs, correcting loop exits and cold misses while eliminating most repeat loop-back bubbles with far less timing cost than the prior static and BTB predictors.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can distinguish correct loop predictions from loop-exit mispredicts.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a one-entry backward-loop predictor lookup on PC equality, select the registered target on a hit, and update the entry from resolved EX branch information.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Latch the IF-stage predicted next PC into ID/EX without changing raw instruction source fields or decoded control semantics.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Expose resolved branch update information and change redirect generation to compare actual next PC against the carried predicted next PC, including loop-exit correction.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire prediction update signals between EX and IF while preserving the nret=1 RVFI port contract and existing stall/flush priorities.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r4s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,21 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\n+title: \"Single-entry loop target predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  The failed predictor attempts show that broad prediction logic loses when it adds immediate decode, target adders, RAM lookup, counters, or same-cycle ID redirect control to the front-end critical path. CoreMark still has repeated loop-back branches that pay the current EX-resolution flush penalty, so the best remaining predictor angle is a much narrower mechanism that only learns the last hot backward branch target and keeps all target computation in EX.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a single-entry last-taken backward-branch predictor updated from resolved EX-stage branches. IF predicts taken only when the current PC exa