{"type":"text","timestamp":1778644968542,"sessionID":"ses_1e07ff8c9ffed3Kqwtnhw7ESyh","part":{"id":"prt_e1f8060330016J4Yd0hf9H6XqZ","messageID":"msg_e1f802d630013JeIHp9L1zDMSm","sessionID":"ses_1e07ff8c9ffed3Kqwtnhw7ESyh","type":"text","text":"The prior predictor regressions consistently point to IF critical-path cost from decode, target adders, RAM/tag logic, and even a single loop compare. I’m writing a narrower predictor hypothesis: a tiny return-target cache for resolved JALR returns, updated in EX, with no IF instruction decode or target arithmetic.","time":{"start":1778644967476,"end":1778644968541},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_093dbdbc12bc7cea016a03f7e76138819aa5f0ae22ecf5eff3","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778644977611,"sessionID":"ses_1e07ff8c9ffed3Kqwtnhw7ESyh","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_0mFHMfbINSqTnTTQZzvrKrnn","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r5s2.yaml\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r5s2\n+title: \"Tiny JALR return target predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior branch predictor attempts lost fitness because they put immediate decode,\n+  target addition, BTB lookup, or loop-PC compare control on the front-end timing\n+  path. CoreMark still pays the existing EX-resolution flush on direct calls,\n+  indirect returns, and other taken JALR instructions, and return targets are often\n+  stable for a given return instruction PC in this small benchmark binary.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a very narrow return-target predictor updated only from resolved EX-stage\n+  JALR return-like instructions, such as JALR x0, x1/x5, 0. Keep target computation\n+  in EX and store the resolved return instruction PC plus actual target in a tiny\n+  one-entry or two-entry table. IF remains mostly sequential and predicts only on\n+  an exact registered PC hit, using the stored target with no instruction decode,\n+  immediate generation, or target add in the fetch path. Carry the predicted next\n+  PC through ID/EX so EX corrects stale entries and non-return JALR cases. This\n+  targets a different CoreMark control-flow penalty than the failed loop predictors\n+  while keeping the predictor small enough to have a plausible Fmax/IPC tradeoff.\n+expected_impact:\n+  fitness_delta_pct: 2\n+  confidence: low\n+changes:\n+  - file: rtl/core_pkg.sv\n+    description: \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX so EX can validate return-target predictions without changing RVFI retirement fields.\"\n+  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Add a tiny registered return-target cache lookup by fetch PC and select the stored target only on an exact hit, leaving the default path as pc+4.\"\n+  - file: rtl/id_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Latch prediction metadata from IF into ID/EX alongside the existing decoded instruction and raw source fields.\"\n+  - file: rtl/ex_stage.sv\n+    description: \"Detect resolved JALR return-like instructions, update the return-target cache with the actual target, and redirect only when the carried prediction differs from the actual next PC.\"\n+  - file: rtl/core.sv\n+    description: \"Wire return predictor update signals from EX to IF while preserving the nret=1 top-level IO contract.\"\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r5s2.yaml","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r5s2.yaml\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r5s2.yaml\n+++ /Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r5s2.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,33 @@\n+id: hyp-20260513-003-r5s2\n+title: \"Tiny JALR return target predictor\"\n+category: predictor\n+motivation: |\n+  Prior branch predictor attempts lost fitness because they put immediate decode,\n+  target addition, BTB lookup, or loop-PC compare control on the front-end timing\n+  path. CoreMark still pays the existing EX-resolution flush on direct calls,\n+  indirect returns, and other taken JALR instructions, and return targets are often\n+  stable for a given return instruction PC in this small benchmark binary.\n+hypothesis: |\n+  Add a very narrow return-target predictor updated only from resolved EX-stage\n+  JALR return-like instructions, such as JALR x0, x1/x5, 0. Keep target com