{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778646596953,"sessionID":"ses_1e0674db0ffeEmw3uLEWkzZ3An","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_dn5xz3N6VpXQbsM0QPqgcX8n","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: id: hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\n2: title: \"Two-entry lookahead hot predictor\"\n3: category: predictor\n4: motivation: |\n5:   The current one-entry lookahead predictor is the first predictor variant that improved fitness because it keeps the current IF next-PC mux free of tag comparisons and target adders. CoreMark still contains nested loops and direct control-flow edges, so a single learned PC can be evicted by another hot edge and lose most of the warm predictor benefit between repeated visits.\n6: hypothesis: |\n7:   Expand the existing registered lookahead predictor in if_stage from one entry to two small entries, updated from the same EX-resolved taken backward branches and direct jumps. While fetching PC N, compare N+4 against both registered entry PCs only to prearm the following cycle; when the predicted instruction is actually fetched, the next-PC mux still consumes only the already-registered armed target. This should reduce predictor thrashing on nested CoreMark loops and call/jump structure without reintroducing the timing pattern that broke current-PC BTBs, static IF decode, ID redirects, or return predictors.\n8: expected_impact:\n9:   fitness_delta_pct: 3\n10:   confidence: medium\n11: changes:\n12:   - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n13:     description: \"Replace the single pred_valid/pred_pc/pred_target entry with two registered entries, add simple replacement on EX updates, and prearm from a two-entry lookahead match while keeping the current next-PC mux driven only by armed_valid_q and armed_target_q.\"\n\n(End of file - total 13 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"id: hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\ntitle: \"Two-entry lookahead hot predictor\"\ncategory: predictor\nmotivation: |\n  The current one-entry lookahead predictor is the first predictor variant that improved fitness because it keeps the current IF next-PC mux free of tag comparisons and target adders. CoreMark still contains nested loops and direct control-flow edges, so a single learned PC can be evicted by another hot edge and lose most of the warm predictor benefit between repeated visits.\nhypothesis: |\n  Expand the existing registered lookahead predictor in if_stage from one entry to two small entries, updated from the same EX-resolved taken backward branches and direct jumps. While fetching PC N, compare N+4 against both registered entry PCs only to prearm the following cycle; when the predicted instruction is actually fetched, the next-PC mux still consumes only the already-registered armed target. This should reduce predictor thrashing on nested CoreMark loops and call/jump structure without reintroducing the timing pattern that broke current-PC BTBs, static IF decode, ID redirects, or return predictors.\nexpected_impact:\n  fitness_delta_pct: 3\n  confidence: medium\nchanges:\n  - file: rtl/if_stage.sv\n    description: \"Replace the single pred_valid/pred_pc/pred_target entry with two registered entries, add simple replacement on EX updates, and prearm from a two-entry lookahead match while keeping the current next-PC mux driven only by armed_valid_q and armed_target_q.\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/hypotheses/hyp-20260513-003-r7s2.yaml","time":{"start":1778646596949,"end":1778646596953}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_08880e4af4c6c506016a03fe43fc9c8198a6e72d004768db13"}},"id":"prt_e1f9939f9001AcTnQZBopTqL78","sessionID":"ses_1e0674db0ffeEmw3uLEWkzZ3An","messageID":"msg_e1f99223f001n9rvrX3dWGSLdR"}}
