{"type":"text","timestamp":1778647764858,"sessionID":"ses_1e055368cffemZ0UAPWBAj72oY","part":{"id":"prt_e1fab05820012hybcDLQrlVT0A","messageID":"msg_e1faaef4b0018g89wk0lDmjPDL","sessionID":"ses_1e055368cffemZ0UAPWBAj72oY","type":"text","text":"The history confirms the only successful predictor so far is the one-entry sequential lookahead predictor; two-entry expansion regressed due to extra arming compares and replacement logic. I’m going to propose a narrower predictor refinement that keeps the single-entry timing shape but improves how it is trained.","time":{"start":1778647762306,"end":1778647764857},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_01c9b3ed715baffd016a0402d235d08198a313da78c6de0cd7","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778647764906,"sessionID":"ses_1e055368cffemZ0UAPWBAj72oY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_cLPBiYL28aEkByPDPwGeSjcW","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","offset":19,"limit":4},"output":"<path>/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Lookahead hot-branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost because the prediction decision sat directly on the current IF next-PC path: immediate decode, target adders, tag compares, or same-cycle ID redirects reduced Fmax more than CoreMark gained from fewer taken-branch bubbles. CoreMark still has hot loop-back branches, so the remaining promising predictor angle is to keep prediction state registered and move the lookup one cycle ahead of the branch fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost because the prediction decision sat directly on the current IF next-PC path: immediate decode, target adders, tag compares, or same-cycle ID redirects reduced Fmax more than CoreMark gained from fewer taken-branch bubbles. CoreMark still has hot loop-back branches, so the remaining promising predictor angle is to keep prediction state registered and move the lookup one cycle ahead of the branch fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry hot control-flow predictor that is updated from EX with the resolved PC and target of taken backward branches and direct jumps, but consume it through a one-cycle sequential lookahead. While fetching PC N, compare the registered predictor PC against N+4 and latch a prearmed prediction for the next sequential fetch; when PC N+4 is fetched on the following cycle, the IF next-PC mux uses only the registered prearmed target, not a same-cycle tag compare or target adder. Carry the predicted next PC with the instruction so EX redirects only on a real mismatch. This should recover loop-back taken-branch bubbles while avoiding the timing pattern that broke the prior IF BTB, static, loop, and return predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can validate a prearmed prediction without c... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Drop dead branch payload\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent micro-optimization attempts show that added front-end logic, broad\\ncontrol repacking, and multiplier restructuring tend to lose Fmax, while\\ntargeted removal or simplification of always-carried datapath logic is the\\nsafer path. In the current bench core, branch resolution is fully completed\\ninside EX: redirect, predictor update, pc_next, and trap handling are all\\nproduced before the EX/MEM register. The EX/MEM payload still carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target even though MEM, WB, RVFI, forwarding, and\\nhazard logic do not consume them.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent micro-optimization attempts show that added front-end logic, broad\\ncontrol repacking, and multiplier restructuring tend to lose Fmax, while\\ntargeted removal or simplification of always-carried datapath logic is the\\nsafer path. In the current bench core, branch resolution is fully completed\\ninside EX: redirect, predictor update, pc_next, and trap handling are all\\nproduced before the EX/MEM register. The EX/MEM payload still carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target even though MEM, WB, RVFI, forwarding, and\\nhazard logic do not consume them.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t and\\ndelete the corresponding EX-stage register assignments. This should reduce\\nthe EX/MEM register by 33 bits, including reset and dmem-stall hold muxing,\\nwithout changing instruction timing, branch redirect behavior, predictor\\nupdates, RVFI pc_wdata, trap behavior, or CoreMark CPI. The change is much\\nnarrower than the prior late-control pruning attempt: it only deletes fields\\nalready proven dead downstream, avoiding new packed-control structs or extra\\nmuxing on hot paths.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the unused branch_taken and branc... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Precompute MEM access descriptor in EX\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest recent non-predictor gain came from simplifying MEM-stage byte-lane muxing, which suggests the load/store formatting path is still important for Tang Nano 20K fitness. The current MEM stage still derives misalignment, byte masks, replicated store data, aligned RVFI addresses, and dmem enables in the same cycle that dmem_rdata is selected and forwarded to writeback. Front-end queues, IF retiming, high-multiply side units, and direct load-data bypassing have already shown poor tradeoffs, so the next structural target should be a no-CPI retiming of an existing hot back-end path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest recent non-predictor gain came from simplifying MEM-stage byte-lane muxing, which suggests the load/store formatting path is still important for Tang Nano 20K fitness. The current MEM stage still derives misalignment, byte masks, replicated store data, aligned RVFI addresses, and dmem enables in the same cycle that dmem_rdata is selected and forwarded to writeback. Front-end queues, IF retiming, high-multiply side units, and direct load-data bypassing have already shown poor tradeoffs, so the next structural target should be a no-CPI retiming of an existing hot back-end path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the address-dependent memory access descriptor generation from MEM into EX, immediately after the effective address is computed. EX should precompute the byte mask, replicated store data, word-aligned RVFI address, memory-misalignment trap bit, and trap-gated control for load/store instructions, then carry those registered fields in EX/MEM. MEM can then drive dmem_wen/dmem_ren, RVFI masks, and store write data mostly from registered descriptor fields while retaining the existing load-data extraction from dmem_rdata. This should shorten the MEM address/control-to-writeback and dmem-enable paths with no CPI cost, while... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"Two-entry lookahead hot predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current one-entry lookahead predictor is the first predictor variant that improved fitness because it keeps the current IF next-PC mux free of tag comparisons and target adders. CoreMark still contains nested loops and direct control-flow edges, so a single learned PC can be evicted by another hot edge and lose most of the warm predictor benefit between repeated visits.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current one-entry lookahead predictor is the first predictor variant that improved fitness because it keeps the current IF next-PC mux free of tag comparisons and target adders. CoreMark still contains nested loops and direct control-flow edges, so a single learned PC can be evicted by another hot edge and lose most of the warm predictor benefit between repeated visits.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Expand the existing registered lookahead predictor in if_stage from one entry to two small entries, updated from the same EX-resolved taken backward branches and direct jumps. While fetching PC N, compare N+4 against both registered entry PCs only to prearm the following cycle; when the predicted instruction is actually fetched, the next-PC mux still consumes only the already-registered armed target. This should reduce predictor thrashing on nested CoreMark loops and call/jump structure without reintroducing the timing pattern that broke current-PC BTBs, static IF decode, ID redirects, or return predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the single pred_valid/pred_pc/pred_target entry with two registered entries, add simple replacement on EX updates, and prearm from a two-entry lookahead match while keeping the current next-PC mux driven only by armed_valid_q and armed_target_q.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"ch... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n\n(End of file - total 22 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Lookahead hot-branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost because the prediction decision sat directly on the current IF next-PC path: immediate decode, target adders, tag compares, or same-cycle ID redirects reduced Fmax more than CoreMark gained from fewer taken-branch bubbles. CoreMark still has hot loop-back branches, so the remaining promising predictor angle is to keep prediction state registered and move the lookup one cycle ahead of the branch fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost because the prediction decision sat directly on the current IF next-PC path: immediate decode, target adders, tag compares, or same-cycle ID redirects reduced Fmax more than CoreMark gained from fewer taken-branch bubbles. CoreMark still has hot loop-back branches, so the remaining promising predictor angle is to keep prediction state registered and move the lookup one cycle ahead of the branch fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry hot control-flow predictor that is updated from EX with the resolved PC and target of taken backward branches and direct jumps, but consume it through a one-cycle sequential lookahead. While fetching PC N, compare the registered predictor PC against N+4 and latch a prearmed prediction for the next sequential fetch; when PC N+4 is fetched on the following cycle, the IF next-PC mux uses only the registered prearmed target, not a same-cycle tag compare or target adder. Carry the predicted next PC with the instruction so EX redirects only on a real mismatch. This should recover loop-back taken-branch bubbles while avoiding the timing pattern that broke the prior IF BTB, static, loop, and return predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can validate a prearmed prediction without c... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Drop dead branch payload\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent micro-optimization attempts show that added front-end logic, broad\\ncontrol repacking, and multiplier restructuring tend to lose Fmax, while\\ntargeted removal or simplification of always-carried datapath logic is the\\nsafer path. In the current bench core, branch resolution is fully completed\\ninside EX: redirect, predictor update, pc_next, and trap handling are all\\nproduced before the EX/MEM register. The EX/MEM payload still carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target even though MEM, WB, RVFI, forwarding, and\\nhazard logic do not consume them.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent micro-optimization attempts show that added front-end logic, broad\\ncontrol repacking, and multiplier restructuring tend to lose Fmax, while\\ntargeted removal or simplification of always-carried datapath logic is the\\nsafer path. In the current bench core, branch resolution is fully completed\\ninside EX: redirect, predictor update, pc_next, and trap handling are all\\nproduced before the EX/MEM register. The EX/MEM payload still carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target even though MEM, WB, RVFI, forwarding, and\\nhazard logic do not consume them.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t and\\ndelete the corresponding EX-stage register assignments. This should reduce\\nthe EX/MEM register by 33 bits, including reset and dmem-stall hold muxing,\\nwithout changing instruction timing, branch redirect behavior, predictor\\nupdates, RVFI pc_wdata, trap behavior, or CoreMark CPI. The change is much\\nnarrower than the prior late-control pruning attempt: it only deletes fields\\nalready proven dead downstream, avoiding new packed-control structs or extra\\nmuxing on hot paths.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the unused branch_taken and branc... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Precompute MEM access descriptor in EX\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest recent non-predictor gain came from simplifying MEM-stage byte-lane muxing, which suggests the load/store formatting path is still important for Tang Nano 20K fitness. The current MEM stage still derives misalignment, byte masks, replicated store data, aligned RVFI addresses, and dmem enables in the same cycle that dmem_rdata is selected and forwarded to writeback. Front-end queues, IF retiming, high-multiply side units, and direct load-data bypassing have already shown poor tradeoffs, so the next structural target should be a no-CPI retiming of an existing hot back-end path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest recent non-predictor gain came from simplifying MEM-stage byte-lane muxing, which suggests the load/store formatting path is still important for Tang Nano 20K fitness. The current MEM stage still derives misalignment, byte masks, replicated store data, aligned RVFI addresses, and dmem enables in the same cycle that dmem_rdata is selected and forwarded to writeback. Front-end queues, IF retiming, high-multiply side units, and direct load-data bypassing have already shown poor tradeoffs, so the next structural target should be a no-CPI retiming of an existing hot back-end path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the address-dependent memory access descriptor generation from MEM into EX, immediately after the effective address is computed. EX should precompute the byte mask, replicated store data, word-aligned RVFI address, memory-misalignment trap bit, and trap-gated control for load/store instructions, then carry those registered fields in EX/MEM. MEM can then drive dmem_wen/dmem_ren, RVFI masks, and store write data mostly from registered descriptor fields while retaining the existing load-data extraction from dmem_rdata. This should shorten the MEM address/control-to-writeback and dmem-enable paths with no CPI cost, while... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"Two-entry lookahead hot predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current one-entry lookahead predictor is the first predictor variant that improved fitness because it keeps the current IF next-PC mux free of tag comparisons and target adders. CoreMark still contains nested loops and direct control-flow edges, so a single learned PC can be evicted by another hot edge and lose most of the warm predictor benefit between repeated visits.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current one-entry lookahead predictor is the first predictor variant that improved fitness because it keeps the current IF next-PC mux free of tag comparisons and target adders. CoreMark still contains nested loops and direct control-flow edges, so a single learned PC can be evicted by another hot edge and lose most of the warm predictor benefit between repeated visits.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Expand the existing registered lookahead predictor in if_stage from one entry to two small entries, updated from the same EX-resolved taken backward branches and direct jumps. While fetching PC N, compare N+4 against both registered entry PCs only to prearm the following cycle; when the predicted instruction is actually fetched, the next-PC mux still consumes only the already-registered armed target. This should reduce predictor thrashing on nested CoreMark loops and call/jump structure without reintroducing the timing pattern that broke current-PC BTBs, static IF decode, ID redirects, or return predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the single pred_valid/pred_pc/pred_target entry with two registered entries, add simple replacement on EX updates, and prearm from a two-entry lookahead match while keeping the current next-PC mux driven only by armed_valid_q and armed_target_q.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"ch... (line truncated to 2000 chars)","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","time":{"start":1778647764874,"end":1778647764905}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_01c9b3ed715baffd016a0402d4c3648198bacc7238b6e131c2"}},"id":"prt_e1fab0f7b0019wPZzbFydE7ozx","sessionID":"ses_1e055368cffemZ0UAPWBAj72oY","messageID":"msg_e1faaef4b0018g89wk0lDmjPDL"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778647765036,"sessionID":"ses_1e055368cffemZ0UAPWBAj72oY","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_J0G1vpmoRyWO5sSJNjkLsXf6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"implementation_notes|lookahead|pred_update|direct jumps|taken backward|regression|-22.20|7.25","path":"/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl","include":"log.jsonl"},"output":"Found 20 matches\n/Users/bonetto/bonetto/auto-arch-tournament/.claude/bench-runs/gpt-5_5_high-rep3/cores/bench/experiments/log.jsonl:\n  Line 1: {\"id\": \"baseline-bench-d11022f\", \"title\": \"Baseline retest for cores/bench\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"outcome\": \"improvement\", \"fitness\": 282.82, \"delta_pct\": 0.0, \"vs_baseline\": 0.0, \"fmax_mhz\": 127.03, \"ipc_coremark\": 2e-06, \"cycles\": 4491485, \"iterations\": 10, \"lut4\": 9563, \"ff\": 1866, \"seeds\": [128.72, 127.03, 123.02], \"formal_passed\": true, \"cosim_passed\": true, \"error\": null, \"implementation_notes\": \"\", \"timestamp\": \"2026-05-13T01:44:34.902179Z\", \"round_id\": 0, \"slot\": 0}\n\n  Line 3: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r1s1\", \"title\": \"Move DIV/REM off the ALU critical path\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current execute stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU, including\\nSystemVerilog division and remainder operators in the same result mux as the\\ncommon RV32I and MUL operations. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely bloats LUT\\nusage and lengthens the EX critical path even though CoreMark is dominated by\\nordinary integer, load/store, branch, and multiply instructions rather than\\ndivide/remainder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current execute stage contains a fully combinational RV32IM ALU, including\\nSystemVerilog division and remainder operators in the same result mux as the\\ncommon RV32I and MUL operations. On the Tang Nano 20K this likely bloats LUT\\nusage and lengthens the EX critical path even though CoreMark is dominated by\\nordinary integer, load/store, branch, and multiply instructions rather than\\ndivide/remainder.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split DIV/DIVU/REM/REMU out of the combinational ALU into a small iterative\\nmulti-cycle M-extension side unit in EX. Keep ADD/SUB/logic/shift/compare and\\nthe MUL-family operations on the existing single-cycle path, but detect divide\\nand remainder opcodes in EX, start the divider, and stall the pipeline until\\nthe result is available. This structural decoupling should reduce the normal\\nALU critical path and LUT pressure with negligible CoreMark CPI cost because\\nrare DIV/REM instructions pay the added latency only when they occur.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 8, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real DIV/REM operators from the combinational ALU path while preserving ALTOPS behavior for formal builds.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Add DIV/REM detection, launch/consume the iterative result, and hold the EX/MEM register while a divide operation is in progress.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\":...\n  Line 4: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r1s2\", \"title\": \"Static backward branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken loop branch or JAL pays a two-instruction flush penalty. CoreMark has tight loops and frequent backward branches, making a very small front-end predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without the LUT and Fmax cost of a larger dynamic predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage core resolves all branches and jumps in EX, so every taken loop branch or JAL pays a two-instruction flush penalty. CoreMark has tight loops and frequent backward branches, making a very small front-end predictor likely to improve iterations per cycle without the LUT and Fmax cost of a larger dynamic predictor.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a static predict-taken path in IF for aligned backward conditional branches and aligned unconditional JAL, while keeping forward conditional branches predicted not-taken and JALR resolved in EX. Carry the predicted next PC through ID/EX, compare it against the actual EX-resolved next PC, and redirect only on mispredict. This should remove most loop-back branch penalties with only immediate decode/add logic in the fetch path and no predictor RAM state.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX pipeline bundles so EX can validate the IF-stage prediction while preserving RVFI pc_wdata semantics.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Decode fetched branch/JAL immediates in IF and choose aligned pc+imm for backward conditional branches and JAL, otherwise pc+4; emit the chosen predicted next PC with the fetched instruction.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Latch the IF-stage predicted next PC into ID/EX alongside the existing decoded instruction metadata.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage....\n  Line 5: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-001-r2s0\", \"title\": \"Collapse ALU multiply products\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The post-DIV baseline still computes three independent 64-bit multiplier\\nproducts in the combinational ALU: unsigned*unsigned, signed*signed, and\\nsigned*unsigned. CoreMark benefits from keeping MUL single-cycle, but the\\nextra high-half multiplier hardware likely costs LUTs, routing, and Fmax on\\nthe Tang Nano 20K even when only one M-extension result is selected.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The post-DIV baseline still computes three independent 64-bit multiplier\\nproducts in the combinational ALU: unsigned*unsigned, signed*signed, and\\nsigned*unsigned. CoreMark benefits from keeping MUL single-cycle, but the\\nextra high-half multiplier hardware likely costs LUTs, routing, and Fmax on\\nthe Tang Nano 20K even when only one M-extension result is selected.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the three parallel ALU multiplier products with one unsigned 32x32\\nproduct plus high-half sign-correction subtractors. The low 32 bits are\\nidentical for MUL under any signedness; MULHU uses the raw high half; MULH\\nsubtracts the opposite operand from the high half for each negative input;\\nand MULHSU subtracts the unsigned multiplier operand when rs1 is negative.\\nThis preserves the existing single-cycle M-extension CPI while reducing\\nreplicated multiplier logic and routing pressure on the ALU result path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Compute one unsigned product and derive MULH/MULHSU high halves with RV32M-correct sign-correction logic instead of instantiating three parallel products.\"}, {\"file\": \"test/test_alu.py\", \"description\": \"Add focused MULH and MULHSU edge vectors covering negative operands, INT_MIN, all-ones, and mixed signed/unsigned correction cases.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"de...\n  Line 6: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-002-r2s1\", \"title\": \"Decoupled fetch skid buffer\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current front end is tightly coupled to the rest of the pipeline: any\\ndmem stall, load-use stall, divide stall, or raw imem-not-ready cycle holds\\nthe PC and prevents useful fetch progress. In the tournament CoreMark mode\\nboth instruction and data ports see random backpressure, so exposed fetch\\nbubbles reduce iterations per cycle even when the instruction port could\\nhave fetched ahead during unrelated back-end stalls.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end is tightly coupled to the rest of the pipeline: any\\ndmem stall, load-use stall, divide stall, or raw imem-not-ready cycle holds\\nthe PC and prevents useful fetch progress. In the tournament CoreMark mode\\nboth instruction and data ports see random backpressure, so exposed fetch\\nbubbles reduce iterations per cycle even when the instruction port could\\nhave fetched ahead during unrelated back-end stalls.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a tiny two-entry fetch skid buffer between IF and ID. The IF stage should\\nkeep issuing sequential fetches while the decode/back-end side is stalled and\\nthere is queue space, and ID should consume from the queue whenever it can\\nadvance. Redirects still flush the queue and restart at the resolved target,\\npreserving the current EX-resolution semantics and RVFI ordering. This\\nstructural decoupling should hide a fraction of random imem stalls behind\\ndmem/load-use/div stalls with modest LUT/FF cost and less timing risk than\\nputting branch prediction logic back on the fetch critical path.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 6, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the purely combinational IF/ID payload with a small valid-ready fetch queue that can fill while ID is stalled, drains to ID when available, and flushes on redirect.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/hazard_unit.sv\", \"description\": \"Base front-end stalls ...\n  Line 7: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260512-003-r2s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny BTB branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so tight CoreMark\\nloops pay a two-instruction redirect penalty on each taken iteration. The prior\\nstatic backward predictor showed that avoiding these penalties can help CPI,\\nbut its IF-stage immediate decode and target add hurt Fmax enough to lose most\\nof the gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so tight CoreMark\\nloops pay a two-instruction redirect penalty on each taken iteration. The prior\\nstatic backward predictor showed that avoiding these penalties can help CPI,\\nbut its IF-stage immediate decode and target add hurt Fmax enough to lose most\\nof the gain.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a small direct-mapped BTB with 2-bit saturating counters, updated only from\\nresolved control-flow instructions in EX. IF predicts taken only on a valid tag\\nhit with a taken counter and uses the stored target, otherwise it fetches pc+4;\\nthis keeps branch immediate decode and target addition out of the fetch path.\\nCarry predicted next-PC metadata through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX redirects only\\nwhen the stored prediction disagrees with the actual resolved next PC. This\\nshould recover most repeated loop-branch and unconditional jump penalties after\\nwarm-up with lower Fmax risk than the failed static predictor.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted next-PC and prediction-valid metadata to the IF/ID and ID/EX bundles.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Implement a small direct-mapped BTB/BHT lookup in IF, select stored targets on confident tag hits, and update entries from EX resolution signals.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/id_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Latch IF prediction metadata into ID/EX without changing raw instruction rs fields or RVFI-visible...\n  Line 8: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r3s0\", \"title\": \"Source-aware load-use interlock\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current load-use hazard compares the prior load destination against both raw rs1 and rs2 bitfields of the following instruction. For many RV32I encodings one or both fields are not architecturally read, so the core can inject a one-cycle bubble after