tructure keeps CPI low but likely puts external instruction-memory output, decoder fanout, and regfile read timing on one FPGA-critical path. Prior fetch-ahead structures lost badly because queue control and prediction logic made the front end more complex; a single registered IF/ID boundary is the minimal structural retiming that targets the same timing path without adding speculation or buffering policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current front end has no real IF/ID register: io_imemData feeds decode, immediate generation, regfile address selection, hazard inputs, and the ID/EX register in the same cycle. That structure keeps CPI low but likely puts external instruction-memory output, decoder fanout, and regfile read timing on one FPGA-critical path. Prior fetch-ahead structures lost badly because queue control and prediction logic made the front end more complex; a single registered IF/ID boundary is the minimal structural retiming that targets the same timing path without adding speculation or buffering policy.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Convert if_stage from a combinational IF/ID payload producer into a simple one-entry registered fetch/decode boundary. The PC still advances sequentially when the front end is not stalled, redirects still override stalls and flush the younger instruction, and ID consumes the registered instruction exactly as today. This should break the imem_data-to-decoder-to-ID/EX critical path and improve Fmax while preserving single-issue throughput; the expected CPI cost is limited to unchanged redirect/load-use behavior rather than the extra queue-control overhead seen in the failed skid-buffer attempt.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta...\n  Line 10: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r3s2\", \"title\": \"ID-stage static control predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so CoreMark loop\\nbacks and direct jumps pay a two-instruction wrong-path flush. Prior IF-stage\\nstatic and BTB predictors showed that eliminating this penalty can help CPI,\\nbut putting immediate decode, target add, tag compare, or predictor RAM lookup\\non the fetch next-PC path costs too much Fmax on Tang Nano 20K.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core resolves every taken branch and jump in EX, so CoreMark loop\\nbacks and direct jumps pay a two-instruction wrong-path flush. Prior IF-stage\\nstatic and BTB predictors showed that eliminating this penalty can help CPI,\\nbut putting immediate decode, target add, tag compare, or predictor RAM lookup\\non the fetch next-PC path costs too much Fmax on Tang Nano 20K.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the lightweight static predictor out of IF and into ID. IF should remain\\na simple sequential pc+4 fetch unless an existing redirect arrives, while ID\\ndecodes the fetched instruction and redirects one stage early for aligned JAL\\nand aligned backward conditional branches. Carry the ID-predicted next PC into\\nEX so the branch/jump resolver redirects only when the actual next PC differs\\nfrom the prediction. This keeps predictor work off the front-end critical path\\nand still saves one of the two taken-control-flow bubbles in CoreMark loops.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add an ID/EX predicted-next-PC field so EX can compare the static ID prediction with the actual resolved next PC.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/core.sv\", \"description\": \"Wire ID-stage prediction redirect signals to IF and route the carried predicted next PC into EX resolution.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Accept an ID-stage prediction redirect with lower priority than EX correctio...\n  Line 11: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r4s0\", \"title\": \"Case-based MEM byte-lane muxes\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current best core already gained by removing rare DIV/REM from the common\\nEX datapath, while recent front-end and multiplier micro-optimizations lost\\nFmax. A lower-risk remaining hot path is the MEM/WB load-data and store-mask\\nlogic: CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the current MEM stage uses variable\\nshifts for byte extraction and byte-lane mask generation in the same cycle\\nthat load data can feed writeback and forwarding.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current best core already gained by removing rare DIV/REM from the common\\nEX datapath, while recent front-end and multiplier micro-optimizations lost\\nFmax. A lower-risk remaining hot path is the MEM/WB load-data and store-mask\\nlogic: CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the current MEM stage uses variable\\nshifts for byte extraction and byte-lane mask generation in the same cycle\\nthat load data can feed writeback and forwarding.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Replace the MEM-stage variable shifts with explicit case muxes indexed by\\naddress bits. Generate byte and halfword load slices directly from\\ndmem_rdata[7:0], [15:8], [23:16], and [31:24], and generate store masks from\\nwidth/address case arms rather than left-shifting a constant. This should map\\nto smaller LUT mux trees on Tang Nano 20K, shorten the dmem_rdata-to-WB and\\naddress-to-mask paths, and preserve the exact RVFI aligned-memory reporting,\\nmisalignment traps, and pipeline timing.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite byte/halfword load extraction and store byte-mask generation as explicit case muxes instead of variable shifts, leaving misalignment gating and RVFI fields unchanged.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Rewrite byte/halfword lo...\n  Line 12: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r4s1\", \"title\": \"Iterative high-half multiply side unit\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The successful DIV/REM side-unit hypothesis showed that this FPGA benefits\\nwhen rare, wide arithmetic is removed from the common EX-stage ALU result\\npath. The current ALU still computes three 64-bit multiply variants every\\ncycle and muxes their high halves alongside the common RV32I and low-half\\nMUL operations. CoreMark should mostly exercise ordinary integer ops and\\nlow-half MUL, while MULH/MULHU/MULHSU are uncommon in compiler output.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The successful DIV/REM side-unit hypothesis showed that this FPGA benefits\\nwhen rare, wide arithmetic is removed from the common EX-stage ALU result\\npath. The current ALU still computes three 64-bit multiply variants every\\ncycle and muxes their high halves alongside the common RV32I and low-half\\nMUL operations. CoreMark should mostly exercise ordinary integer ops and\\nlow-half MUL, while MULH/MULHU/MULHSU are uncommon in compiler output.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Keep ALU_MUL as a single-cycle low-half multiply, but move ALU_MULH,\\nALU_MULHU, and ALU_MULHSU into a small multi-cycle high-multiply side unit\\nowned by EX, using the same stall/consume pattern already proven for DIV/REM.\\nThe common ALU path then only needs the low-half unsigned product for MUL and\\nno longer carries signed high-product result muxing on every instruction.\\nRare high-half multiply instructions pay a short structural stall, but the\\nexpected CoreMark mix should recover more Fmax than it loses in IPC.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 4, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/alu.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove real ALU_MULH, ALU_MULHU, and ALU_MULHSU product logic from the normal combinational ALU path while preserving RISCV_FORMAL_ALTOPS substitutions.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Detect high-half multiply operations, start a small side unit, stall EX until the r...\n  Line 13: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r4s2\", \"title\": \"Single-entry loop target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The failed predictor attempts show that broad prediction logic loses when it adds immediate decode, target adders, RAM lookup, counters, or same-cycle ID redirect control to the front-end critical path. CoreMark still has repeated loop-back branches that pay the current EX-resolution flush penalty, so the best remaining predictor angle is a much narrower mechanism that only learns the last hot backward branch target and keeps all target computation in EX.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The failed predictor attempts show that broad prediction logic loses when it adds immediate decode, target adders, RAM lookup, counters, or same-cycle ID redirect control to the front-end critical path. CoreMark still has repeated loop-back branches that pay the current EX-resolution flush penalty, so the best remaining predictor angle is a much narrower mechanism that only learns the last hot backward branch target and keeps all target computation in EX.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a single-entry last-taken backward-branch predictor updated from resolved EX-stage branches. IF predicts taken only when the current PC exactly matches the stored branch PC, using the already-registered target from the entry; all other fetches stay simple pc+4, and no instruction immediate decode or branch target addition occurs in IF. Carry the predicted next PC through IF/ID and ID/EX so EX redirects only when the actual resolved next PC differs, correcting loop exits and cold misses while eliminating most repeat loop-back bubbles with far less timing cost than the prior static and BTB predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can distinguish correct loop predictions from loop-exit mispredicts.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"descri...\n  Line 14: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r5s0\", \"title\": \"Drop regfile bulk reset\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"The current core still synchronously clears all 32 integer registers on reset.\\nThat adds reset fanout and reset muxing across roughly a thousand register-file\\nbits, even though RV32I does not architecturally require x1-x31 to reset to\\nzero and benchmark software initializes the registers it depends on. Prior\\nmicro-opt attempts that touched fetch prediction or multiplier structure paid\\ncontrol/datapath costs, so a contained timing cleanup with no CPI effect is a\\nbetter fit for the next slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current core still synchronously clears all 32 integer registers on reset.\\nThat adds reset fanout and reset muxing across roughly a thousand register-file\\nbits, even though RV32I does not architecturally require x1-x31 to reset to\\nzero and benchmark software initializes the registers it depends on. Prior\\nmicro-opt attempts that touched fetch prediction or multiplier structure paid\\ncontrol/datapath costs, so a contained timing cleanup with no CPI effect is a\\nbetter fit for the next slot.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the bulk reset loop from the integer register file while preserving x0\\nhardwiring, normal synchronous writes, and the same-cycle write-first read\\nbypass. This should reduce reset-net fanout and per-bit reset control in a hot\\nalways-on structure, giving nextpnr more freedom to place the regfile and its\\nbypass muxes. CoreMark CPI should be unchanged because the pipeline behavior,\\nforwarding, RVFI retirement, and writeback timing are identical after reset.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/reg_file.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the synchronous reset clearing loop for x1-x31, keep x0 reads forced to zero, and preserve the write-first bypass and write gating semantics.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{...\n  Line 16: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r5s2\", \"title\": \"Tiny JALR return target predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictor attempts lost fitness because they put immediate decode,\\ntarget addition, BTB lookup, or loop-PC compare control on the front-end timing\\npath. CoreMark still pays the existing EX-resolution flush on direct calls,\\nindirect returns, and other taken JALR instructions, and return targets are often\\nstable for a given return instruction PC in this small benchmark binary.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior branch predictor attempts lost fitness because they put immediate decode,\\ntarget addition, BTB lookup, or loop-PC compare control on the front-end timing\\npath. CoreMark still pays the existing EX-resolution flush on direct calls,\\nindirect returns, and other taken JALR instructions, and return targets are often\\nstable for a given return instruction PC in this small benchmark binary.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a very narrow return-target predictor updated only from resolved EX-stage\\nJALR return-like instructions, such as JALR x0, x1/x5, 0. Keep target computation\\nin EX and store the resolved return instruction PC plus actual target in a tiny\\none-entry or two-entry table. IF remains mostly sequential and predicts only on\\nan exact registered PC hit, using the stored target with no instruction decode,\\nimmediate generation, or target add in the fetch path. Carry the predicted next\\nPC through ID/EX so EX corrects stale entries and non-return JALR cases. This\\ntargets a different CoreMark control-flow penalty than the failed loop predictors\\nwhile keeping the predictor small enough to have a plausible Fmax/IPC tradeoff.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX so EX can validate return-target predictions without changing RVFI retirement fields.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Ad...\n  Line 17: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r6s0\", \"title\": \"Prune late pipeline control fields\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent attempts show that adding front-end prediction or arithmetic side-control tends to cost more Fmax than it saves, while the successful MEM-stage case-mux change improved fitness by simplifying always-active datapaths. The current pipeline still carries the full decoded ctrl_t through EX/MEM and MEM/WB even though many fields are dead after EX, and almost all fields are dead after MEM. Those unnecessary bits add flops, reset/hold muxing, struct routing, and fanout on hot writeback and forwarding control.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent attempts show that adding front-end prediction or arithmetic side-control tends to cost more Fmax than it saves, while the successful MEM-stage case-mux change improved fitness by simplifying always-active datapaths. The current pipeline still carries the full decoded ctrl_t through EX/MEM and MEM/WB even though many fields are dead after EX, and almost all fields are dead after MEM. Those unnecessary bits add flops, reset/hold muxing, struct routing, and fanout on hot writeback and forwarding control.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Split the late pipeline control payload into narrower MEM-stage and WB-stage control structs. EX/MEM only needs memory access width/sign, mem read/write, reg_write, mem_to_reg, and trap state; MEM/WB only needs reg_write, mem_to_reg, and trap state because RVFI memory masks/data have already been materialized. Removing unused branch, jump, ALU-op, operand-select, AUIPC/LUI, and memory-format bits from late pipeline registers should reduce Tang Nano 20K placement/routing pressure and shorten small but always-active control muxes without changing instruction timing, RVFI fields, or CoreMark CPI.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add narrow ex_mem and mem_wb control typedefs, change ex_mem_t and m...\n  Line 18: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r6s1\", \"title\": \"MEM load-data bypass to EX\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always injects a bubble for a load-use pair,\\neven when the data memory is ready and the load data is available during the\\nfollowing MEM cycle. CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the recent MEM-stage\\nbyte-lane improvement indicates this benchmark is sensitive to the memory\\ndatapath. Prior structural frontend decoupling and prediction attempts paid\\ntoo much fetch-path timing cost, so a backend bypass is a more focused IPC\\nimprovement.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current five-stage pipeline always injects a bubble for a load-use pair,\\neven when the data memory is ready and the load data is available during the\\nfollowing MEM cycle. CoreMark is load/store heavy, and the recent MEM-stage\\nbyte-lane improvement indicates this benchmark is sensitive to the memory\\ndatapath. Prior structural frontend decoupling and prediction attempts paid\\ntoo much fetch-path timing cost, so a backend bypass is a more focused IPC\\nimprovement.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a direct MEM-stage load-result bypass into the EX operand forwarding\\nnetwork. When a load sits in EX/MEM and a younger instruction in ID/EX reads\\nthe same rd, EX should use the current MEM load_data instead of stalling for\\nthe value to reach MEM/WB. The bypass must be disabled for misaligned/trapping\\nloads so dependent instructions retain the old architectural register value,\\nand dmem backpressure should still freeze the pipeline until valid load data\\nis available. This removes the normal one-cycle load-use penalty without\\nadding branch prediction, fetch queues, or nret changes.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 5, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/mem_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Expose the combinational aligned load_data value and a bypass-valid signal gated off for misaligned or trapping loads.\"}, {\"file\": \"rtl/ex_stage.sv\", \"descripti...\n  Line 19: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r6s2\", \"title\": \"Lookahead hot-branch predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost because the prediction decision sat directly on the current IF next-PC path: immediate decode, target adders, tag compares, or same-cycle ID redirects reduced Fmax more than CoreMark gained from fewer taken-branch bubbles. CoreMark still has hot loop-back branches, so the remaining promising predictor angle is to keep prediction state registered and move the lookup one cycle ahead of the branch fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Prior predictor attempts lost because the prediction decision sat directly on the current IF next-PC path: immediate decode, target adders, tag compares, or same-cycle ID redirects reduced Fmax more than CoreMark gained from fewer taken-branch bubbles. CoreMark still has hot loop-back branches, so the remaining promising predictor angle is to keep prediction state registered and move the lookup one cycle ahead of the branch fetch.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Add a one-entry hot control-flow predictor that is updated from EX with the resolved PC and target of taken backward branches and direct jumps, but consume it through a one-cycle sequential lookahead. While fetching PC N, compare the registered predictor PC against N+4 and latch a prearmed prediction for the next sequential fetch; when PC N+4 is fetched on the following cycle, the IF next-PC mux uses only the registered prearmed target, not a same-cycle tag compare or target adder. Carry the predicted next PC with the instruction so EX redirects only on a real mismatch. This should recover loop-back taken-branch bubbles while avoiding the timing pattern that broke the prior IF BTB, static, loop, and return predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 2, \"confidence\": \"low\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Add predicted-next-PC metadata to IF/ID and ID/EX bundles so EX can validate a prearmed prediction without c...\n  Line 20: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-001-r7s0\", \"title\": \"Drop dead branch payload\", \"category\": \"micro_opt\", \"motivation\": \"Recent micro-optimization attempts show that added front-end logic, broad\\ncontrol repacking, and multiplier restructuring tend to lose Fmax, while\\ntargeted removal or simplification of always-carried datapath logic is the\\nsafer path. In the current bench core, branch resolution is fully completed\\ninside EX: redirect, predictor update, pc_next, and trap handling are all\\nproduced before the EX/MEM register. The EX/MEM payload still carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target even though MEM, WB, RVFI, forwarding, and\\nhazard logic do not consume them.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"Recent micro-optimization attempts show that added front-end logic, broad\\ncontrol repacking, and multiplier restructuring tend to lose Fmax, while\\ntargeted removal or simplification of always-carried datapath logic is the\\nsafer path. In the current bench core, branch resolution is fully completed\\ninside EX: redirect, predictor update, pc_next, and trap handling are all\\nproduced before the EX/MEM register. The EX/MEM payload still carries\\nbranch_taken and branch_target even though MEM, WB, RVFI, forwarding, and\\nhazard logic do not consume them.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Remove the unused branch_taken and branch_target fields from ex_mem_t and\\ndelete the corresponding EX-stage register assignments. This should reduce\\nthe EX/MEM register by 33 bits, including reset and dmem-stall hold muxing,\\nwithout changing instruction timing, branch redirect behavior, predictor\\nupdates, RVFI pc_wdata, trap behavior, or CoreMark CPI. The change is much\\nnarrower than the prior late-control pruning attempt: it only deletes fields\\nalready proven dead downstream, avoiding new packed-control structs or extra\\nmuxing on hot paths.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 1, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/core_pkg.sv\", \"description\": \"Remove the unused branch_taken and branc...\n  Line 21: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-002-r7s1\", \"title\": \"Precompute MEM access descriptor in EX\", \"category\": \"structural\", \"motivation\": \"The strongest recent non-predictor gain came from simplifying MEM-stage byte-lane muxing, which suggests the load/store formatting path is still important for Tang Nano 20K fitness. The current MEM stage still derives misalignment, byte masks, replicated store data, aligned RVFI addresses, and dmem enables in the same cycle that dmem_rdata is selected and forwarded to writeback. Front-end queues, IF retiming, high-multiply side units, and direct load-data bypassing have already shown poor tradeoffs, so the next structural target should be a no-CPI retiming of an existing hot back-end path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The strongest recent non-predictor gain came from simplifying MEM-stage byte-lane muxing, which suggests the load/store formatting path is still important for Tang Nano 20K fitness. The current MEM stage still derives misalignment, byte masks, replicated store data, aligned RVFI addresses, and dmem enables in the same cycle that dmem_rdata is selected and forwarded to writeback. Front-end queues, IF retiming, high-multiply side units, and direct load-data bypassing have already shown poor tradeoffs, so the next structural target should be a no-CPI retiming of an existing hot back-end path.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Move the address-dependent memory access descriptor generation from MEM into EX, immediately after the effective address is computed. EX should precompute the byte mask, replicated store data, word-aligned RVFI address, memory-misalignment trap bit, and trap-gated control for load/store instructions, then carry those registered fields in EX/MEM. MEM can then drive dmem_wen/dmem_ren, RVFI masks, and store write data mostly from registered descriptor fields while retaining the existing load-data extraction from dmem_rdata. This should shorten the MEM address/control-to-writeback and dmem-enable paths with no CPI cost, while...\n  Line 22: {\"id\": \"hyp-20260513-003-r7s2\", \"title\": \"Two-entry lookahead hot predictor\", \"category\": \"predictor\", \"motivation\": \"The current one-entry lookahead predictor is the first predictor variant that improved fitness because it keeps the current IF next-PC mux free of tag comparisons and target adders. CoreMark still contains nested loops and direct control-flow edges, so a single learned PC can be evicted by another hot edge and lose most of the warm predictor benefit between repeated visits.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": {\"motivation\": \"The current one-entry lookahead predictor is the first predictor variant that improved fitness because it keeps the current IF next-PC mux free of tag comparisons and target adders. CoreMark still contains nested loops and direct control-flow edges, so a single learned PC can be evicted by another hot edge and lose most of the warm predictor benefit between repeated visits.\\n\", \"hypothesis\": \"Expand the existing registered lookahead predictor in if_stage from one entry to two small entries, updated from the same EX-resolved taken backward branches and direct jumps. While fetching PC N, compare N+4 against both registered entry PCs only to prearm the following cycle; when the predicted instruction is actually fetched, the next-PC mux still consumes only the already-registered armed target. This should reduce predictor thrashing on nested CoreMark loops and call/jump structure without reintroducing the timing pattern that broke current-PC BTBs, static IF decode, ID redirects, or return predictors.\\n\", \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"changes\": [{\"file\": \"rtl/if_stage.sv\", \"description\": \"Replace the single pred_valid/pred_pc/pred_target entry with two registered entries, add simple replacement on EX updates, and prearm from a two-entry lookahead match while keeping the current next-PC mux driven only by armed_valid_q and armed_target_q.\"}]}, \"expected_impact\": {\"fitness_delta_pct\": 3, \"confidence\": \"medium\"}, \"ch...","metadata":{"matches":20,"truncated":false},"title":"implementation_notes|lookahead|pred_update|direct jumps|taken backward|regression|-22.20|7.25","time":{"start":1778647765019,"end":1778647765034}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_01c9b3ed715baffd016a0402d4c3888198a032f150799abe07"}},"id":"prt_e1fab0f8c001ipbNHtjOz2F55h","sessionID":"ses_1e055368cffemZ0UAPWBAj72oY","messageID":"msg_e1faaef4b0018g89wk0lDmjPDL"}}
